{"title_page": "Charlie Powell (presenter)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Charlie Powell\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Charlie Powell from Instagram.jpg\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Powell at Kiss studios, London\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Charlotte Grace May Powell\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1994|05|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Stroud, Gloucestershire]], England\n| origin           = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{death date and age|2017|08|21|1952|09|21|df=y}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            = \n| occupation       = [[Disc Jockey]]\n| instrument       = \n| years_active     = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label            = \n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Charlie Powell''' (born Charlotte Grace May Powell, 30 May 1994) is an English [[radio personality]], [[radio producer]] and [[DJ]] from [[Cornwall]], best known for her Saturday evening show on [[Kiss (UK radio station)|Kiss]], part of the [[Kiss Network]], which airs from 9-12pm on Saturday nights.\n\n==Early life==\n\nCharlie was born in [[Stroud]], Gloucestershire on 30 May 1994 to Steven Powell (born 18 April 1960) and Sarah Powell (n\u00e9e Battishill, born 24 September 1969). The family moved to [[Penryn, Cornwall|Penryn]], in 1997. Charlotte was educated at [[Penryn College]] where she became interested in radio, joining the school's Radio Club and becoming involved with [[Source FM]], a local community radio. She undertook work experience at [[Pirate FM]]. After leaving college, she studied at [[University of Westminster]], [[Harrow, London|Harrow]], where she was a Programme Director at Smoke Radio, the university's student radio station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://smoke.media/radio/|title=Smoke Radio homepage|website=Smoke Radio|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n[[File:Charlotte Powell at work, Kiss, London, 2019.png|thumb|Powell recording at Kiss, London]]At university, Charlie served several [[internships]] with production companies such as [[Somethin' Else (content agency)|Somethin' Else]], The Big Idea,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tbimedia.co.uk/|title=TBI media Home page|website=The Big Idea|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Grape,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wearegrape.com/|title=Grape Home page|website=Grape|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> [[Rinse FM]], Pirate Radio again and [[MTA Records]]. Some of this was within the [[BBC]], including [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]], where she was a production assistant, helping with shows from luminaries such as [[Annie Nightingale]] and [[Craig Charles]]. She started broadcasting at [[Roundhouse (venue)|Roundhouse]], a famous london venue, noted for its radio station for young talent. \nIn 2015, she started producing shows for [[Kiss Fresh]], part of the [[Bauer Media Group]] and broadcast her first professional shows on Saturday mornings. She soon began filling in on [[Kiss (UK radio station)|Kiss]] and producing shows on that station. She broadcast her first Saturday  night show in 2019, taking over from Steve Smart.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Steve Smart homepage.\n| publisher=Steve Smart\n| url =https://stevesmart.net}}</ref> That year, she hosted the [[Gay Pride|Pride]] afterparty, at London's [[Covent Garden]].\n\n==Other Activities==\nShe is also a [[voice-over|Voice over]] artist and she occasionally performs as a club DJ, mainly in London.\nCharlie is a regular judge at the Student Radio Awards;.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Student Radio Awards homepage.\n| publisher=Student Radio Association.\n| url =https://www.studentradio.org.uk/awards}}</ref><ref>[[Student Radio Association|Student Radio Association Wikipedia page]]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCharlie is single. She has a sister, Harriet Daisy May Powell, born 25 January 1996, [[Stroud]], Gloucestershire.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://planetradio.co.uk/kiss/shows/charliepowell/ Charlie Powell Kiss profile]\n*[https://www.instagram.com/hicharliepowell/ Charlie Powell Instagram]\n*[https://twitter.com/hicharliepowell/ Charlie Powell Twitter]\n\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix    = \n| name                =Charlie Powell\n| honorific_suffix    = \n| image               =[[File:Charlie Powell from Instagram.jpg|thumb|Charlie Powell at Kiss]]\n| image_upright       = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Charlie Powell at Kiss studios, London.\n| background          =  non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| birth_name          = Charlotte Grace May Powell\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1994|05|30|df=y}} \n| birth_place         = [[Stroud]], [[Gloucestershire]], England\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|2017|08|21|1952|09|21|df=y}} -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = \n| occupation          = [[Disc Jockey]]\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label               = \n| website             =\n\n| module              = \n| module2             = \n| module3             = \n}}\n\n'''Charlie Powell''' (born Charlotte Grace May Powell, 30 May 1994) is an English [[radio personality]], [[radio producer]] and [[DJ]] from [[Cornwall]], best known for her Saturday evening show on [[Kiss (UK radio station)|Kiss]], part of the [[Kiss Network]], which airs from 9-12pm on Saturday nights.\n\n==Early life==\n\nCharlie was born in [[Stroud]], Gloucestershire on 30 May 1994 to Steven Powell (born 18 April 1960) and Sarah Powell (n\u00e9e Battishill, born 24 September 1969). The family moved to [[Penryn, Cornwall|Penryn]], in 1997. Charlotte was educated at [[Penryn College]] where she became interested in radio, joining the school's Radio Club and becoming involved with [[Source FM]], a local community radio. She undertook work experience at [[Pirate FM]]. After leaving college, she studied at [[University of Westminster]], [[Harrow, London|Harrow]], where she was a Programme Director at Smoke Radio, the university's student radio station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://smoke.media/radio/|title=Smoke Radio homepage|website=Smoke Radio|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n[[File:Charlotte Powell at work, Kiss, London, 2019.png|thumb|left|Charlie Powell recording at Kiss, London]]At university, Charlie served several [[internships]] with production companies such as [[Somethin' Else (content agency)|Somethin' Else]], The Big Idea,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tbimedia.co.uk/|title=TBI media Home page|website=The Big Idea|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Grape,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wearegrape.com/|title=Grape Home page|website=Grape|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> [[Rinse FM]], Pirate Radio again and [[MTA Records]]. Some of this was within the [[BBC]], including [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]], where she was a production assistant, helping with shows from luminaries such as [[Annie Nightingale]] and [[Craig Charles]]. She started broadcasting at [[Roundhouse (venue)|Roundhouse]], a famous london venue, noted for its radio station for young talent. \nIn 2015, she started producing shows for [[Kiss Fresh]], part of the [[Bauer Media Group]] and broadcast her first professional shows on Saturday mornings. She soon began filling in on [[Kiss (UK radio station)|Kiss]] and producing shows on that station. She broadcast her first Saturday  night show in 2019, taking over from Steve Smart.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Steve Smart homepage.\n| publisher=Steve Smart\n| url =https://stevesmart.net}}</ref> That year, she hosted the [[Gay Pride|Pride]] afterparty, at London's [[Covent Garden]].\n\n==Other Activities==\nShe is also a [[voice-over|Voice over]] artist and she occasionally performs as a club DJ, mainly in London.\nCharlie is a regular judge at the Student Radio Awards;.<ref>{{cite web\n| title =Student Radio Awards homepage.\n| publisher=Student Radio Association.\n| url =https://www.studentradio.org.uk/awards}}</ref><ref>[[Student Radio Association|Student Radio Association Wikipedia page]]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCharlie is single. She has a sister, Harriet Daisy May Powell, born 25 January 1996, [[Stroud]], Gloucestershire.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n[https://planetradio.co.uk/kiss/shows/charliepowell/ Charlie Powell Kiss profile]\n\n[https://www.instagram.com/hicharliepowell/ Charlie Powell Instagram]\n\n[https://twitter.com/hicharliepowell/ Charlie Powell Twitter]\n\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlie_Powell_(presenter)"}
{"title_page": "Johannes Wilde", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{use list-defined references|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Johannes Wilde\n| image              = Johannes Wilde.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Portrait photograph of Johannes Wilde by Ursula Pariser\n| birth_name         = J\u00e1nos Wilde\n| birth_date         = 2 July 1891\n| birth_place        = [[Budapest]], Hungary\n| death_date         = 13 September 1970\n| death_place        = [[Dulwich]], England\n| nationality        = Hungarian, Austrian, British\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = art historian\n| known_for          = catalogue of [[Michelangelo]] drawings in the [[National Gallery]], London\n}}\n\n'''Johannes Wilde''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (2 July 1891 \u2013 13 September 1970) was a Hungarian art historian and teacher of art history. He later became an Austrian, and then a British, citizen. He was a noted expert on the drawings of [[Michelangelo]]. Wilde was a pioneer of the use of [[X-rays]] as a tool for the study of both the creation and the state of conservation of paintings. From 1948 to 1958 he was deputy director of the [[Courtauld Institute of Art]] in London.<ref name=court/><ref name=dnb/>\n\n==Life==\nJohannes Wilde was born J\u00e1nos Wilde on 2 July 1891 in [[Budapest]], Hungary. He was the last of six children of Richard Wilde (died 1912) and his wife Rosa ''n\u00e9e'' Somj\u00e1gy (died 1928). From 1909 to 1914 he studied art, philosophy and archeology at the [[University of Budapest]] and then from 1915 to 1917 studied for a doctorate under [[Max Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]] at the [[University of Vienna]], defending his thesis ''summa cum laude'' in July 1918. He returned to Budapest and was until 1922 an assistant to [[Simon Meller]] in the department of prints and drawings of the [[Museum of Fine Arts (Budapest)|Museum of Fine Arts]].\n\nIn the brief period of the [[Hungarian Soviet Republic]] of [[B\u00e9la Kun]] in 1919, Wilde worked with [[Frederick Antal]] on the sequestration of privately owned works of art of national significance.\n\nMax Dvo\u0159\u00e1k died in February 1921, and in 1922 Wilde moved permanently to Vienna in order to work with [[Carl Maria Swoboda]] on a collected edition of Dvo\u0159\u00e1k's writings. This was published between 1924 and 1929. He became an Austrian citizen in 1928, and on 6 February 1930 married the art historian Julia Gy\u00e1rf\u00e1s.<ref name=dnb/>\n\n==Theatrum Pictorium==\nFrom 1923 Wilde worked as an assistant Keeper, and later as a Keeper, at the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] of Vienna, where he worked principally on [[Italian Renaissance]] paintings. Many of the paintings in the collections of the museum were in a poor state of conservation in the [[Hofburg]].<ref name=hirst/> He carefully researched and catalogued the Italian paintings, many of which were documented in [[David Teniers the Younger]]'s [[Theatrum Pictorium]], though with incorrect attributions. \n\nIt was Wilde who discovered that the hitherto separate paintings by [[Antonello da Messina]] in the collection \"[[:File:Antonello da Messina - Pala di San Cassiano Detail- San Nicholas - Kunsthistorisches Museum Vienna.jpg|St. Nicolas and a Female Saint]]\" (attributed by Teniers to Bellini), \"[[:File:Antonello da Messina 063.jpg|The Virgin and Child Enthroned]]\", and \"[[:File:Antonello da Messina 008.jpg|St. Dominic and St. Ursula]]\", were all fragments of one altarpiece and he oversaw the reconconstruction of the [[San Cassiano Altarpiece]] in 1928.<ref>J. Wilde, \"Pala di San Cassiano\" Rekonstruktionsversuch, Jahrbuch der Kunsthist. Samml. in Wien, n. s., III (1929), pp. 57-72</ref>\n\n==X-rays==\nBy about 1928 Wilde and the restorer Sebastian Isepp were using [[X-radiation]] as a systematic aid to understanding both the physical condition of paintings and the artistic processes by which those paintings had been created. At first they made use of the facilities of the R\u00f6ntgenologisches Institut of [[Vienna University]], but in 1930 an X-ray laboratory was installed at the Kunsthistorisches Museum. While Wilde was not the first to use X-rays to examine pictures, this was the first such laboratory in Europe. He first published his findings on [[The Gypsy Madonna]] and [[The Three Philosophers]]'<ref name=hirst/> In the next eight years Wilde made more than 1000 X-ray photographs of works in the museum. He also maintained a steady flow of scholarly publications.<ref name=hirst/>\n\n==Britain==\nAfter the [[Anschluss]], the annexation of Austria into the German [[Third Reich]] on 12 March 1938, Wilde's Hungarian Jewish wife Julia was at risk. With the help of friends including Count [[Antoine Seilern]], the couple left Vienna for the Netherlands in April 1939 to visit an art exhibition; from there they flew to England, where they stayed at the home of [[Sir Kenneth Clark]], director of the [[National Gallery]] and [[Surveyor of the King's Pictures]]. \n\nWilde soon went to [[Aberystwyth]] to work on Seilern's pictures, which had been sent to the [[National Library of Wales]] for safety at the beginning of the [[Second World War]]. He also worked on the pictures of the National Gallery, which were in the same building. The [[British Museum]] collection of Italian drawings was also housed there and, through [[Arthur Ewart Popham]], Wilde was asked in June 1940 by the Trustees of the museum to start work on cataloguing them too.<ref name=\"dnb\" />\n\nIn the same year, in what Kenneth Clark describes as a \"revolting incident\", Wilde was charged with signalling to enemy submarines, interned in a concentration camp, and deported to another camp in Canada, where he barely survived.<ref name=dnb/><ref name=clark/>\n\n==Publications==\nThe publications of Johannes Wilde include:\n*Max Dvo\u0159\u00e1k; Carl Maria Swoboda and Johannes Wilde (eds.), ''Kunstgeschichte als Geistesgeschichte. Studien zur abendl\u00e4ndischen Kunstentwicklung''. M\u00fcnchen: R. Piper, 1924\n*{{long dash}}, ''Das R\u00e4tsel der Kunst der Br\u00fcder van Eyck: mit einem Anhang \u00fcber die Anf\u00e4nge der holl\u00e4ndischen Malerei''. M\u00fcnchen: R. Piper, 1925\n*{{long dash}}, ''Geschichte der italienischen Kunst im Zeitalter der Renaissance akademische Vorlesungen'' (2 volumes). M\u00fcnchen: R. Piper, 1927\u201328\n*{{long dash}}, ''Gesammelte Aufs\u00e4tze zur Kunstgeschichte''. M\u00fcnchen: R. Piper, 1929\n*Arthur Ewart Popham and Johannes Wilde, ''The Italian Drawings of the XV and XVI Centuries ... at Windsor Castle''. (catalogue, with reproductions; the sections relating to Michelangelo and his school by J. Wilde, translated by J. Leveen) London: Phaidon Press, 1949\n*Johannes Wilde, ''Italian drawings in the Department of Prints and Drawings in the British Museum: Michelangelo and his studio''. London: Trustees of the British Museum, 1953\n*{{long dash}} and Arthur Ewart Popham, ''Italian drawings in the Department of Prints and Drawings in the British Museum: Artists working in Parma in the sixteenth century; Correggio, Anselmi, Rondani, Gatti, Gambara, Orsi, Parmigianino, Bedoli, Bertoja''. London: Trustees of the British Museum, 1967\n*{{long dash}} ''Venetian art from Bellini to Titian''. Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1974. {{ISBN|019817327X}} (posthumous publication)\n*{{long dash}}; John Shearman and Michael Hirst (eds.), ''Michelangelo: six lectures''. Oxford studies in the history of art and architecture. Oxford: Clarendon Press; New York: Oxford University Press, 1978. {{ISBN|9780198173168}} (posthumous publication)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=clark>Kenneth Clark (June 1961). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/873321 \"Johannes Wilde\"]. ''The Burlington Magazine'', Special Issue in Honour of Professor Johannes Wilde. '''103''', 699: 205 {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=court>Julie Tancell (2000). [http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cats/2/1818.htm Wilde, Johannes (1891-1970): Identity statement]. ''Courtauld Institute of Art''. Accessed May 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=dnb>Dennis Farr, [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36895 \"Wilde, Johannes (1891\u20131970)\"]. ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004; online edition, Jan 2011. doi:10.1093/ref:odnb/36895.</ref>\n\n<ref name=hirst>Michael Hirst (March 1971). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/876585 \"Obituary: Johannes Wilde\"]. ''The Burlington Magazine'', '''113''', 816: 155-157 {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilde, Johannes}}\n[[Category:Hungarian art historians]]\n[[Category:Austrian art historians]]\n[[Category:British art historians]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Courtauld Institute of Art]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{use list-defined references|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Johannes Wilde\n| image              = Johannes Wilde.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Portrait photograph of Johannes Wilde by Ursula Pariser\n| birth_name         = J\u00e1nos Wilde\n| birth_date         = 2 July 1891\n| birth_place        = [[Budapest]], Hungary\n| death_date         = 13 September 1970\n| death_place        = [[Dulwich]], England\n| nationality        = Hungarian, Austrian, British\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = art historian\n| known_for          = catalogue of [[Michelangelo]] drawings in the [[National Gallery]], London\n}}\n\n'''Johannes Wilde''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (2 July 1891 \u2013 13 September 1970) was a Hungarian art historian and teacher of art history. He later became an Austrian, and then a British, citizen. He was a noted expert on the drawings of [[Michelangelo]]. Wilde was a pioneer of the use of [[X-rays]] as a tool for the study of both the creation and the state of conservation of paintings. From 1948 to 1958 he was deputy director of the [[Courtauld Institute of Art]] in London.<ref name=court/><ref name=dnb/>\n\n==Life==\nJohannes Wilde was born J\u00e1nos Wilde on 2 July 1891 in [[Budapest]], Hungary. He was the last of six children of Richard Wilde (died 1912) and his wife Rosa ''n\u00e9e'' Somlyaky (died 1928). From 1909 to 1914 he studied art, philosophy and archeology at the [[University of Budapest]] and then from 1915 to 1917 studied for a doctorate under [[Max Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]] at the [[University of Vienna]], defending his thesis ''summa cum laude'' in July 1918. He returned to Budapest and was until 1922 an assistant to [[Simon Meller]] in the department of prints and drawings of the [[Museum of Fine Arts (Budapest)|Museum of Fine Arts]].\n\nIn the brief period of the [[Hungarian Soviet Republic]] of [[B\u00e9la Kun]] in 1919, Wilde worked with [[Frederick Antal]] on the sequestration of privately owned works of art of national significance.\n\nMax Dvo\u0159\u00e1k died in February 1921, and in 1922 Wilde moved permanently to Vienna in order to work with [[Carl Maria Swoboda]] on a collected edition of Dvo\u0159\u00e1k's writings. This was published between 1924 and 1929. He became an Austrian citizen in 1928, and on 6 February 1930 married the art historian Julia Gy\u00e1rf\u00e1s.<ref name=dnb/>\n\n==Theatrum Pictorium==\nFrom 1923 Wilde worked as an assistant Keeper, and later as a Keeper, at the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] of Vienna, where he worked principally on [[Italian Renaissance]] paintings. Many of the paintings in the collections of the museum were in a poor state of conservation in the [[Hofburg]].<ref name=hirst/> He carefully researched and catalogued the Italian paintings, many of which were documented in [[David Teniers the Younger]]'s [[Theatrum Pictorium]], though with incorrect attributions. \n\nIt was Wilde who discovered that the hitherto separate paintings by [[Antonello da Messina]] in the collection \"[[:File:Antonello da Messina - Pala di San Cassiano Detail- San Nicholas - Kunsthistorisches Museum Vienna.jpg|St. Nicolas and a Female Saint]]\" (attributed by Teniers to Bellini), \"[[:File:Antonello da Messina 063.jpg|The Virgin and Child Enthroned]]\", and \"[[:File:Antonello da Messina 008.jpg|St. Dominic and St. Ursula]]\", were all fragments of one altarpiece and he oversaw the reconconstruction of the [[San Cassiano Altarpiece]] in 1928.<ref>J. Wilde, \"Pala di San Cassiano\" Rekonstruktionsversuch, Jahrbuch der Kunsthist. Samml. in Wien, n. s., III (1929), pp. 57-72</ref>\n\n==X-rays==\nBy about 1928 Wilde and the restorer Sebastian Isepp were using [[X-radiation]] as a systematic aid to understanding both the physical condition of paintings and the artistic processes by which those paintings had been created. At first they made use of the facilities of the R\u00f6ntgenologisches Institut of [[Vienna University]], but in 1930 an X-ray laboratory was installed at the Kunsthistorisches Museum. While Wilde was not the first to use X-rays to examine pictures, this was the first such laboratory in Europe. He first published his findings on [[The Gypsy Madonna]] and [[The Three Philosophers]]'<ref name=hirst/> In the next eight years Wilde made more than 1000 X-ray photographs of works in the museum. He also maintained a steady flow of scholarly publications.<ref name=hirst/>\n\n==Britain==\nAfter the [[Anschluss]], the annexation of Austria into the German [[Third Reich]] on 12 March 1938, Wilde's Hungarian Jewish wife Julia was at risk. With the help of friends including Count [[Antoine Seilern]], the couple left Vienna for the Netherlands in April 1939 to visit an art exhibition; from there they flew to England, where they stayed at the home of [[Sir Kenneth Clark]], director of the [[National Gallery]] and [[Surveyor of the King's Pictures]]. \n\nWilde soon went to [[Aberystwyth]] to work on Seilern's pictures, which had been sent to the [[National Library of Wales]] for safety at the beginning of the [[Second World War]]. He also worked on the pictures of the National Gallery, which were in the same building. The [[British Museum]] collection of Italian drawings was also housed there and, through [[Arthur Ewart Popham]], Wilde was asked in June 1940 by the Trustees of the museum to start work on cataloguing them too.<ref name=\"dnb\" />\n\nIn the same year, in what Kenneth Clark describes as a \"revolting incident\", Wilde was charged with signalling to enemy submarines, interned in a concentration camp, and deported to another camp in Canada, where he barely survived.<ref name=dnb/><ref name=clark/>\n\n==Publications==\nThe publications of Johannes Wilde include:\n*Max Dvo\u0159\u00e1k; Carl Maria Swoboda and Johannes Wilde (eds.), ''Kunstgeschichte als Geistesgeschichte. Studien zur abendl\u00e4ndischen Kunstentwicklung''. M\u00fcnchen: R. Piper, 1924\n*{{long dash}}, ''Das R\u00e4tsel der Kunst der Br\u00fcder van Eyck: mit einem Anhang \u00fcber die Anf\u00e4nge der holl\u00e4ndischen Malerei''. M\u00fcnchen: R. Piper, 1925\n*{{long dash}}, ''Geschichte der italienischen Kunst im Zeitalter der Renaissance akademische Vorlesungen'' (2 volumes). M\u00fcnchen: R. Piper, 1927\u201328\n*{{long dash}}, ''Gesammelte Aufs\u00e4tze zur Kunstgeschichte''. M\u00fcnchen: R. Piper, 1929\n*Arthur Ewart Popham and Johannes Wilde, ''The Italian Drawings of the XV and XVI Centuries ... at Windsor Castle''. (catalogue, with reproductions; the sections relating to Michelangelo and his school by J. Wilde, translated by J. Leveen) London: Phaidon Press, 1949\n*Johannes Wilde, ''Italian drawings in the Department of Prints and Drawings in the British Museum: Michelangelo and his studio''. London: Trustees of the British Museum, 1953\n*{{long dash}} and Arthur Ewart Popham, ''Italian drawings in the Department of Prints and Drawings in the British Museum: Artists working in Parma in the sixteenth century; Correggio, Anselmi, Rondani, Gatti, Gambara, Orsi, Parmigianino, Bedoli, Bertoja''. London: Trustees of the British Museum, 1967\n*{{long dash}} ''Venetian art from Bellini to Titian''. Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1974. {{ISBN|019817327X}} (posthumous publication)\n*{{long dash}}; John Shearman and Michael Hirst (eds.), ''Michelangelo: six lectures''. Oxford studies in the history of art and architecture. Oxford: Clarendon Press; New York: Oxford University Press, 1978. {{ISBN|9780198173168}} (posthumous publication)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=clark>Kenneth Clark (June 1961). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/873321 \"Johannes Wilde\"]. ''The Burlington Magazine'', Special Issue in Honour of Professor Johannes Wilde. '''103''', 699: 205 {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=court>Julie Tancell (2000). [http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cats/2/1818.htm Wilde, Johannes (1891-1970): Identity statement]. ''Courtauld Institute of Art''. Accessed May 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=dnb>Dennis Farr, [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36895 \"Wilde, Johannes (1891\u20131970)\"]. ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004; online edition, Jan 2011. doi:10.1093/ref:odnb/36895.</ref>\n\n<ref name=hirst>Michael Hirst (March 1971). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/876585 \"Obituary: Johannes Wilde\"]. ''The Burlington Magazine'', '''113''', 816: 155-157 {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilde, Johannes}}\n[[Category:Hungarian art historians]]\n[[Category:Austrian art historians]]\n[[Category:British art historians]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Courtauld Institute of Art]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n", "name_user": "R\u00e9kuli", "label": "safe", "comment": "mother's maiden name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Wilde"}
{"title_page": "Elsie Muller-McLave", "text_new": "{{short description|American speed skater}}\n{{Infobox speed skater\n| name           = Elsie Muller-McLave\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| headercolor    = #d7ecff\n| country        = United States\n| club           = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1894|11|22|}}<ref name=findgrave /> or {{Birth date|1895|11|25|}}<ref name=teamusa />\n| birth_place    = [[Brooklyn]], United States<ref name=findgrave />\n| death_date     = 26 October 1867<ref name=findgrave /><ref name=speedskatingmuseum>[http://speedskatingmuseum.org/wp/elsie-muller-mclave/]</ref>\n| death_place    = [[Dobbs Ferry]], Westchester County, United States\n| height         = \n| weight \t = \n| turnedpro      = \n| retired        = \n|medaltemplates=\n\n}}\n'''Elsie Muller-McLave''' (born 22 November 1894<ref name=findgrave>[https://nl.findagrave.com/memorial/195673562/elsie-mclave]</ref> or 25 November 1895<ref>[https://www.teamusa.org/US-Speedskating/About/Hall-of-Fame-Content/Skaters/Elsie-Muller-McLave]</ref>; died 26 October 1867<ref name=findgrave />) was a female [[United States|American]] [[speed skater]].\n\nDuring her career, she became a National and North American Outdoor and Indoor Champion. Her best season was in 1931. The year later she represented the United States at the 1932 Olympic Games.<ref name=teamusa>[https://www.teamusa.org/US-Speedskating/About/Hall-of-Fame-Content/Skaters/Elsie-Muller-McLave]</ref> She competed in all the three women's [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics|speed skating events at the 1932 Winter Olympics]] which were held as [[demonstration sport]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080410085042/http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1932/1932w.pdf Official Olympic Report 1932]</ref> She finished fifth in the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 500 metres|500 metres event]]. She didn't finish the qualification round of the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 1000 metres|1000 metres event]] and competed in the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1500 metres event]] but was eliminated in the heats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-1500-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 1,500 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-1000-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 1,000 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-500-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 500 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> As it were demonstration events, she didn't get a medal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/women-s-speed-skating-makes-games-debut|title=Women\u2019s speed skating makes Games debut|date=October 23, 2017|website=International Olympic Committee}}</ref>\n\nShe retained her amateur status. She trained speed skating on the [[Hudson River]] and reservoirs. She was a contemporary of [[Kit Klein]] and [[Elizabeth Dubois]].<ref name=speedskatingmuseum />\n\nShe was inducted to the National Speedskating Hall of Fame on 18 May 1968 in [[St. Louis, Missouri]].<ref name=teamusa />\n\n==Personal life==\nHer father was Albert Muller (1857\u20131926) and mother was Thekla Muller (1857\u20131931). She was married in 1929 with Archibald Carlisle McLave (1893\u20131971). She is buried on the [[Mount Hope Cemetery]] in [[Hastings-on-Hudson]], United States.<ref name=findgrave />\n\nTo earn money, she worked as a secretary.<ref name=speedskatingmuseum />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muller-McLave, Elsie}}\n[[Category:Olympic speed skaters of the United States]]\n[[Category:Speed skaters at the 1932 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:American female speed skaters]]\n[[Category:1867 deaths]]\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brooklyn]]\n\n{{US-speed-skating-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American speed skater}}\n{{Infobox speed skater\n| name           = Elsie Muller-McLave\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| headercolor    = #d7ecff\n| country        = United States\n| club           = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1894|11|22|}}<ref name=findgrave /> or {{Birth date|1895|11|25|}}<ref name=teamusa />\n| birth_place    = [[Brooklyn]], United States<ref name=findgrave />\n| death_date     = 26 October 1867<ref name=findgrave /><ref name=speedskatingmuseum>[http://speedskatingmuseum.org/wp/elsie-muller-mclave/]</ref>\n| death_place    = [[Dobbs Ferry]], Westchester County, United States\n| height         = \n| weight \t = \n| turnedpro      = \n| retired        = \n|medaltemplates=\n\n}}\n'''Elsie Muller-McLave''' (born 22 November 1894<ref name=findgrave>[https://nl.findagrave.com/memorial/195673562/elsie-mclave]</ref> or 25 November 1895<ref>[https://www.teamusa.org/US-Speedskating/About/Hall-of-Fame-Content/Skaters/Elsie-Muller-McLave]</ref>; died 26 October 1967<ref name=findgrave />) was a female [[United States|American]] [[speed skater]].\n\nDuring her career, she became a National and North American Outdoor and Indoor Champion. Her best season was in 1931. The year later she represented the United States at the 1932 Olympic Games.<ref name=teamusa>[https://www.teamusa.org/US-Speedskating/About/Hall-of-Fame-Content/Skaters/Elsie-Muller-McLave]</ref> She competed in all the three women's [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics|speed skating events at the 1932 Winter Olympics]] which were held as [[demonstration sport]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080410085042/http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1932/1932w.pdf Official Olympic Report 1932]</ref> She finished fifth in the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 500 metres|500 metres event]]. She didn't finish the qualification round of the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 1000 metres|1000 metres event]] and competed in the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1500 metres event]] but was eliminated in the heats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-1500-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 1,500 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-1000-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 1,000 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-500-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 500 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> As it were demonstration events, she didn't get a medal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/women-s-speed-skating-makes-games-debut|title=Women\u2019s speed skating makes Games debut|date=October 23, 2017|website=International Olympic Committee}}</ref>\n\nShe retained her amateur status. She trained speed skating on the [[Hudson River]] and reservoirs. She was a contemporary of [[Kit Klein]] and [[Elizabeth Dubois]].<ref name=speedskatingmuseum />\n\nShe was inducted to the National Speedskating Hall of Fame on 18 May 1968 in [[St. Louis, Missouri]].<ref name=teamusa />\n\n==Personal life==\nHer father was Albert Muller (1857\u20131926) and mother was Thekla Muller (1857\u20131931). She was married in 1929 with Archibald Carlisle McLave (1893\u20131971). She is buried on the [[Mount Hope Cemetery]] in [[Hastings-on-Hudson]], United States.<ref name=findgrave />\n\nTo earn money, she worked as a secretary.<ref name=speedskatingmuseum />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muller-McLave, Elsie}}\n[[Category:Olympic speed skaters of the United States]]\n[[Category:Speed skaters at the 1932 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:American female speed skaters]]\n[[Category:1867 deaths]]\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brooklyn]]\n\n{{US-speed-skating-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SportsOlympic", "label": "safe", "comment": "8", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elsie_Muller-McLave"}
{"title_page": "Intellivision Amico", "text_new": "{{Infobox information appliance\n| name = Intellivision Amico\n| title = \n| aka = \n| logo = Intellivision_Amico_Logo.jpeg\n| logo_alt = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| caption = \n| developer = [[Intellivision#Intellivision Entertainment|Intellivision Entertainment]]\n| manufacturer = \n| family = \n| type = [[Home video game console]]\n| generation = [[Home video game console#Future|Ninth generation]]\n| release date = {{ubl|{{start date and age|2020|10|10}}}}\n| retail availability = \n| lifespan = \n| price = US$249 [[To be announced|TBC]]<br>US$279 [[To be announced|TBC]] (Limited Editions)<br>US$299 (Founder's Edition)<br>\n| discontinued = \n| units sold = \n| units shipped = \n| media = [[Digital distribution of video games|digital downloads]]\n| os = Custom [[Android (operating system)|Android]]/[[Linux]] operating system\n| power = 12V power<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\">{{cite web |title=Amico Tech Specs \u2014 Intellivision Entertainment |url=https://www.intellivisionamico.com/amico-tech-specs |publisher=Intellivision Entertainment |accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n| soc = \n| cpu = 8 core 1.8GHz CPU<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| memory = 2 GB [[Random-access memory|RAM]]<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| storage = 16 GB [[Flash memory|flash memory]], [[SD card|SD]], USB storage<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| memory card = \n| display = [[HDMI]] <small>(1080p)</small><ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| graphics = \n| sound = \n| input = \n| controllers = Intellivision Amico controller,<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref> Android/iOS device\n| camera = \n| touchpad = \n| connectivity = [[Bluetooth]], [[Wi-Fi]], [[Radio-frequency identification|RFID]], [[USB]]<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| currentfw = \n| platform = \n| service = \n| dimensions = {{convert|11|xx|9.5|xx|2.5|in|mm|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| weight = \n| topgame = \n| compatibility = \n| predecessor = [[Mattel Intellivision]]\n| successor = \n| related = \n| website = {{url|www.intellivisionamico.com}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Intellivision Amico''' is an upcoming [[video game console]] produced by [[Intellivision#Intellivision Entertainment|Intellivision Entertainment]]. It is set to launch in [[North America]], the [[United Kingdom]], the rest of [[Europe]] and the [[MENA]] region on October 10, 2020 with an expected retail price of approximately US$249.<ref name=\"Initial Details\">{{cite web |title=October 2018 Press Release |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/fb1de7_c9b4346bc0784a8689ed35d4adb67e73.pdf |publisher=Intellivision Entertainment |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"5 Colors\">{{cite web |title=Intellivision Reveals 5 Colors for the New Amico Console |url=https://geektyrant.com/news/intellivision-reveals-5-colors-for-the-new-amico-console |publisher=Geek Tyrant |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Intellivision Entertainment\">{{cite web |title=Intellivision Entertainment |url=https://www.intellivisionamico.com/ |publisher=Intellivision Entertainment |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> The console is slated to include six games preloaded at launch with an additional 40 titles available at that time.<ref name=\"Rebirth\">{{cite web |last1=Takahashi |first1=Dean |title=Intellivision Entertainment prepares for its rebirth on 10-10-20 |url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/06/21/intellivision-entertainment-prepares-for-its-rebirth-on-10-10-20/ |publisher=Venture Beat |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Concept==\nThe Intellivision Amico will mostly feature [[2D computer graphics|2D]] and [[2.5D]] games only. [[3D computer graphics|3D]] games will be allowed, as long as they are easy to play and easy to learn. Intellivision Entertainment is providing studios with any resources they need to develop games to put in their curated library of games. All games must have features exclusive to the console, and must be rated E or E10+ by the [[Entertainment Software Rating Board|ESRB]], or PEGI 3 or PEGI 7 by [[Pan European Game Information|PEGI]]. Intellivision Entertainment plan to release a mixture of completely new games, updated classic games and motion control games for the Amico. Updated versions of many of the popular classic Intellivision games will be available with improved graphics and sound and, unlike previous Intellivision compilations, will include some previous third-party licenses, such as ''[[Tron: Deadly Discs]]''. New versions of several classic Atari games, as well as games from [[Imagic]] and arcade classics such as ''[[Moon Patrol]]'' and ''[[BurgerTime]]'' are expected around launch. Downloadable games will cost between US2.99 and US$9.99. Physical editions with [[RFID]] will be available at retail for approximately US$30.<ref name=\"Intellivision Entertainment Announce Amico\">{{cite web |last1=Williams |first1=Carl |title=Intellivision Entertainment Announce Amico Console |url=https://steemit.com/games/@triverse/intellivision-entertainment-announce-amico-console |publisher=steemit.com |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"First Look\">{{cite web |last1=Pelone |first1=Anthony |title=First Look at Intellivision Amico |url=https://www.heypoorplayer.com/2018/10/20/first-look-intellivision-amico-console/ |publisher=heypoorplayer.com |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"FAQ\">{{cite web |title=FAQ \u2014 Intellivision Entertainment |url=https://www.intellivisionamico.com/faq |publisher=Intellivision Entertainment |accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Intellivision revealed their new Amico console\">{{cite web |last1=Borge |first1=Michael |title=Intellivision revealed their new Amico console - Daily Gaming Report |url=https://dailygamingreport.co.uk/latest-gaming-news/intellivision-revealed-their-new-amico-console/ |publisher=Daily Gaming Report |accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref> The Amico's goal is to return to family gaming and \"[[Cooperative gameplay#Couch co-op & online co-op modes|couch co-op]]\" among people in the same location which the company feels has been lost in modern gaming and web-based multiplayer.<ref name=\"CB cites Amico reveal\">{{cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2018/10/21/intellivision-amico-console-announced-release-date-details/ |date=October 20, 2018 |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |last=Fischer |first=Tyler |website=Comicbook.com |title=Intellivision Amico Console Officially Announced, Release Date Revealed}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Development===\nIn May 2018, [[Tommy Tallarico]] announced his plans to launch a new Intellivision console and formed a new company, Intellivision Entertainment, serving as president.<ref name=\"Tallarico Named President\">{{cite web |title=May 2018 Press Release |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/fb1de7_2f64f4a070254b628e99dd64b277f7fb.pdf |publisher=Intellivision Entertainment |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/05/29/intellivsion-lives-tommy-tallarico-will-relaunch-1980s-console/ |title=Intellivision lives: Tommy Tallarico will relaunch 1980s console |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |date=May 29, 2018 |website=[[VentureBeat]]|access-date=May 29, 2018}}</ref>  Intellivision Productions was renamed Blue Sky Rangers Inc. and their video game intellectual property was transferred to the new Intellivision Entertainment.<ref name=\"Reveal Extensive Details\">{{cite web |title=September 2019 Press Release |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/fb1de7_d8afc34cc0b84293b90e9c16ab563499.pdf |publisher=Intellivision Entertainment |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bsr2018\">{{cite web |last1=Roney |first1=Steve |title=Intellivision Productions, Blue Sky Rangers and Intellivision Entertainment |url=http://atariage.com/forums/topic/285395-intellivision-productions-blue-sky-rangers-and-intellivision-entertainment/ |website=atariage |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>  \n\nAt the Portland Retro Gaming Expo in October 2018 the new Intellivision console was officially unveiled, including its name and launch date of October 10, 2020. Developer kits were expected to go out in Summer 2019.<ref name=\"CB cites Amico reveal\"/>\n\nIn May 2019 Intellivision Entertainment revealed its first major console exclusive title, announcing that it had assembled ten members of the original ''[[Earthworm Jim (video game)|Earthworm Jim]]'' team to create a third installment in the franchise in honor of its 25th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web |title=May 2019 Press Release |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/fb1de7_af823002d3f947a7b04d0e335e2da8c3.pdf |publisher=Intellivision Entertainment |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Earthworm Jim game in development\">{{cite web |last1=Hall |first1=Charlie |title=Earthworm Jim game in development for the new Intellivision console |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/5/1/18525333/new-earthworm-jim-game-platform-intellivision |publisher=Polygon |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref> The following month, the company debuted the functioning Amico hardware behind closed doors at [[E3 2019]], allowing industry insiders to play in-development games on one of the functional console variants, and try out the compatible phone controller [[mobile app]].<ref name=\"The Intellivision Amico is Real\">{{cite web |last1=Franzese |first1=Tomas |title=The Intellivision Amico is Real and its Goals Are Commendable |url=https://www.dualshockers.com/the-intellivision-amico-preview-e3-2019/ |publisher=Dual Shockers |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nAt [[Gamescom]] in [[Cologne]], [[Germany]] in August 2019 Tommy Tallarico debuted a trailer that contained in-game footage running on the Amico hardware to the public for the first time.<ref name=\"New Trailer\">{{cite web |title=Intellivision Entertainment Launches New Trailer for Their Upcoming Amico Video Game Console |url=https://www.retrogamenetwork.com/2019/08/19/intellivision-entertainment-launches-new-trailer-for-their-upcoming-amico-video-game-console/ |publisher=Retro Game Network |accessdate=August 22, 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, Tommy Tallarico attended Insomnia Dubai, a gaming convention held in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]], to announce they set up an office in Dubai to launch the Amico in the MENA region on the same day as North America and Europe.<ref name=\"GN cites Amico MENA\">{{cite web|last=Hamad |first=Marwa |url=https://gulfnews.com/going-out/events/insomnia-dubai-supercars-and-gaming-announcements-on-day-one-1.67199184 |title=Insomnia Dubai: Supercars and gaming announcements on day one |work=[[Gulf News]] |date=October 17, 2019 |accessdate=October 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Hardware==\n===Console===\n[[Image:00000000Amico.jpg|thumb|330x330px|Intellivision Amico console and controllers, Woodgrain Edition]]\nThe console features Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, RFID, HDMI out, an SD card slot, and three USB ports, two of which are for charging, and the remaining of which is for expandable storage.<ref name=\"Intellivision plans comeback\">{{cite web |last1=Hall |first1=Charlie |title=Intellivision plans comeback with a new console called Amico in 2020 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/10/22/18008970/intellivision-amico-console-announcement-release-date-price |publisher=Polygon |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref> The body also features a built-in LED ambient lighting system that can change pattern and color in response to gameplay, known as Interactive Guidance Lighting.<ref name=\"It\u2019s Game\">{{cite web |last1=Santa Maria |first1=Alex |title=It\u2019s Game On For Intellivision\u2019s Forthcoming Amico Console |url=https://www.mandatory.com/culture/1474437-intellivision-amico-console |publisher=mandatory.com |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref> This feature is intended to make playing games on the console \"fun and memorable\" while also helping guide players in an interactive way.<ref name=\"Intellivision Entertainment\"></ref>\n===Controller===\n{{Infobox information appliance\n| name                = Intellivision Amico controller\n| title               = \n| aka                 = \n| logo                = \n| logo_alt            = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = \n| caption             = \n| developer           = [[Intellivision#Intellivision Entertainment|Intellivision Entertainment]]\n| manufacturer        = \n| family              = \n| type                = [[Video game controller]]\n| generation          = [[Home video game console#Future|Ninth generation]]\n| release date        = {{ubl|{{start date and age|2020|10|10}}}}\n| retail availability =\n| lifespan            = \n| price               = \n| discontinued        = \n| units sold          = \n| units shipped       = \n| media               = \n| os                  = \n| power               = USB-C host powered<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| soc                 = \n| cpu                 = Unknown CPU<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| memory              = Unknown memory<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| storage             = \n| memory card         = \n| display             = {{convert|3.2|in|mm|2|abbr=on}} 4:3 TFT LCD [[Capacitive sensing|capacitive]] [[touchscreen]]<ref name=\"Capacitive Touchscreen\">{{cite web |title=Intellivision Amico Controller Detailed, First Pack-In Game Revealed |url=https://techraptor.net/gaming/news/intellivision-amico-controller-detailed-first-pack-in-game-revealed |publisher=TechRaptor |last=Adams |first=Robert N. |date=9 December 2019 |accessdate=9 February 2020}}</ref>, full-color, 320 \u00d7 240 [[Graphics display resolution#320 \u00d7 240 (QVGA)|QVGA]]<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref><ref name=\"Tommy Tallarico is making a lot of noise about Intellivision\">{{cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2020/01/12/tommy-tallarico-is-making-a-lot-of-noise-about-intellivision/ |title=Tommy Tallarico is making a lot of noise about Intellivision &#124; VentureBeat |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |date=January 12, 2020 |website=[[VentureBeat]]|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> @ 125 ppi\n| graphics            = \n| sound               = Speaker, microphone<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| input               = * Touchscreen<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n* [[Gyroscope]]<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n* [[Accelerometer]]<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n* 64-way [[Pressure sensor|pressure-sensitive]] directional disc<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n* 5 \u00d7 buttons<br><small>(four shoulder buttons, home button)</small><ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| controllers         = \n| camera              = \n| touchpad            = \n| connectivity        = [[Bluetooth]], [[Wi-Fi]], [[Radio-frequency identification|RFID]], [[USB-C]]<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| currentfw           =\n| platform            = \n| service             = \n| dimensions          = {{convert|6|xx|2.75|xx|1|in|mm|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref>\n| weight              = \n| topgame             = \n| compatibility       = \n| predecessor         = [[Intellivision#Game controller|Intellivision controller]]\n| successor           = \n| related             = \n| website             = \n}}\n\nThe Intellivision Amico comes bundled with two controllers. The controllers can charge wirelessly when they are placed into their cradle on top of the console, charge using a wired USB-C connection, or charge using both methods at the same time. They feature Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, RFID, speakers, a microphone, an accelerometer, [[force feedback]], and a gyroscope. They also feature a {{convert|3.2|in|mm|2|abbr=on}} full-color touch screen, four oversized shoulder buttons, a home button and a 64-way pressure-sensitive directional disc<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref><ref name=\"Amico Gamescom 2019 Trailer\">{{cite web |last1=Battikh |first1=Rany |title=Intellivision Amico Gamescom 2019 Trailer |url=https://www.retrorgb.com/intellivision-amico-gamescom-2019-trailer.html |publisher=retrorgb.com |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"What the Hell\">{{cite web |last1=Diaz |first1=Jesus |title=What the Hell Is the New Intellivision Console? |url=https://www.tomsguide.com/us/intellivision-amico-release-date-price,news-28367.html |publisher=tomsguide.com |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> surrounded by a ring of LEDs.<ref name=\"Meet Amico\u2122 - LED Disc Ring (test 2.18)\">{{cite web |title=Meet Amico\u2122 - LED Disc Ring (test 2.18) - YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OQJ1PX1vTYE |publisher=Intellivision Entertainment |accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> The controllers come with wrist straps<ref name=\"Amico Tech Specs\"></ref> to prevent them from flying away during game action if not held securely. Up to six additional players can connect, with players able to use a free controller [[Mobile app|smartphone app]] in place of an Amico controller when needed.<ref name=\"Geek Links\">{{cite web |last1=Owens |first1=Skip |title=Geek Links: Intellivision Amico Announcement |url=https://geekdad.com/2018/10/geek-links-intellivision-amico-announcement/ |publisher=geekdad.com |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Games==\n{{Expand list|date=January 2020}}\nTommy Tallarico, president of Intellivision Entertainment, has said the games available for the Amico will be about 20% updated and re-imagined versions of classic video games, 20% original new games, 20% sports and recreation, 20% board/dice/card/word/puzzle games, and 20% educational. All games will be both single player and multiplayer, with some games allowing up to eight players, simultaneously, using controllers and/or mobile phones. Some games will have motion control, utilizing the accelerometer and gyroscope of the controller. Some games will have the Karma Gaming Engine, a feature intended to provide players of all skill levels with a fair level of competition against each other by dynamically adjusting the difficulty for players based on how well they are doing in the game. Six games will come included with the Amico, and it will have about thirty games available at launch. Five of the six included games have been announced as ''Skiing'', ''Astrosmash'', ''Shark! Shark!'', ''Cornhole'', and ''Farkle''.<ref name=\"5free\">{{cite web |title=Intellivision Amico Pack-in announcement |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nh6NSLwmamQ |publisher=Intellivision Entertainment |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brutalgamer.com/2019/06/04/intellivision-bringing-22-games-to-e3/|title=Intellivision bringing 22 games to E3|date=2019-06-04|website=Brutal Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref><ref name=\"Intellivision Entertainment prepares for its rebirth on 10-10-20\" /><ref name=\"The Intellivision Amico is Real\" /><ref name=\"Intellivision Amico Controller Detailed, First Pack-In Game Revealed\" /><ref name=\"FAQ\"></ref>\n\nThe following games have been announced to be released for the Intellivision Amico:\n<br>''&#42; unofficial name, subject to change''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" id=\"softwarelist\"\n!Title ({{table row counter|id=softwarelist}})\n!Genre\n!Developer\n!Release date\n|-\n|''10 Yard Fight''\n|[[Sports game|Sports]]\n|\n|2020/21\n|-\n|''Archon''\n|[[Strategy video game|Strategy]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|''Armor Battle''\n|[[Action game|Action]]\n|\n|2020\n|-\n|''Asteroids''\n|[[Shooter game|Shooter]], [[Arcade_game#Arcade_genre|arcade]]\n|\n|2020\n|-\n|''Astrosmash''\n|[[Shooter game|Shooter]]\n|Rogue Rocket Games\n|2020\n|-\n|''Auto Racing''\n|[[Racing video game|Racing]]\n|\n|2020\n|-\n|''B-17 Bomber''\n|[[Action game|Action]]\n|\n|2020/21\n|-\n|''Back Talk Party''&#42; \n|[[Party_game#Video_games|Party]]\n|\n|2020\n|-\n|''Bad Dudes''\n|[[Beat 'em up]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|''Baseball''&#42;\n|[[Sports game|Sports]]\n|\n|2020/21\n|-\n|''Beauty and t