{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saudi Arabia", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Saudi Arabia}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saudi Arabia\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| first_case      = [[Qatif]]\n| arrival_date    = 2 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=02|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]] via [[Iran]], [[Bahrain]], [[Oman]], [[Egypt]], [[France]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| recovery_cases  = 328<ref name=\"sg-24march\"/>\n| deaths          = 21<ref name=\"sg-24march\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 1885<ref name=\"sg-24march\">{{cite news|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/591187/SAUDI-ARABIA/Saudi-Arabia-confirms-first-corona-death-205-new-cases-detected|title=Saudi Arabia confirms first corona death, 205 new cases detected|work=Saudi Gazette|date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324164533/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/591187/SAUDI-ARABIA/Saudi-Arabia-confirms-first-corona-death-205-new-cases-detected|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/events/covid-19/Pages/2020.aspx|website\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 Coronavirus Pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Saudi Arabia]] on March 2, 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{further|Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Saudi Arabia medical cases chart}}\n\n===March 2020===\n*On 2 March 2020, [[Saudi Arabia]] confirmed its first case, a Saudi national returning from [[Iran]] via [[Bahrain]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1635781/saudi-arabia |title=Saudi Arabia announces first case of coronavirus |date=2020-03-02 |access-date=2 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302170439/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1635781/saudi-arabia |archive-date=2 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n*On 4 March, Saudi Arabia reported a second coronavirus case, a companion of the first, who crossed the [[King_Fahd_Causeway|causeway]] from Bahrain without disclosing that he had visited Iran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1636926/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia detects second coronavirus case|website=Arab News|date=2020-03-04|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305103618/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1636926/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*On 5 March, Saudi Arabia's [[Ministry of Health (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Health]] announced three new cases of coronavirus; two of which are a couple who traveled from Iran via [[Kuwait]] and one, another companion of the first and second cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637311/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia announces three more cases of coronavirus|website=Arab News|date=2020-03-05|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307035753/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637311/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*On 6 March, the Ministry of Health announced a further two cases, both being female. One was from Iran via Bahrain and the other was from [[Najaf]], [[Iraq]] through the [[UAE|Emirates]]. Both did not tell the authorities where they had been and thus, were let in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638111/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia announces 2 new cases of coronavirus coming from Iran, Iraq|website=Arab News|date=2020-03-07|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308152845/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638111/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*On 8 March, the Ministry of Health announced 4 more cases. Three of the four patients are citizens who were in contact with previous infected cases arriving from Iran, and the fourth case is a citizen arriving from Iran via the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638471/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia announces 4 new coronavirus cases|website=Arab News|date=2020-03-08|access-date=2020-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308203441/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638471/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*On 9 March, Saudi authorities announced the discovery of four more new coronavirus cases. The new cases include a Saudi national, two Bahrainis, and an American. All the new cases have been quarantined in [[Qatif]] and [[Riyadh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/590618|title=Saudi Arabia discovers 4 more virus cases, suspends travel to 9 countries|website=Arab News|date=2020-03-09|access-date=2020-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310202407/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/590618|archive-date=2020-03-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On 10 March, the Ministry of Health announced 5 more cases, bringing the total to 20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arab.news/cdzr4|title=Saudi health ministry announces five new coronavirus cases|date=2020-03-10|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n*On 11 March, the Ministry of Health announced 1 more case, an Egyptian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/coronavirus/2020/03/11/Saudi-Arabia-reports-new-coronavirus-case-in-Egyptian-citizen-total-up-to-21.html|title=SSaudi Arabia reports new coronavirus case in Egyptian traveler, total up to 21|date=2020-03-11|website=alarabiya|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321052007/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/coronavirus/2020/03/11/Saudi-Arabia-reports-new-coronavirus-case-in-Egyptian-citizen-total-up-to-21.html|archive-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, the Ministry further announced 24 more cases, 21 of which are Egyptians who had been in contact with a person who previously tested positive, taking the country's total to 45.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1640286/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia announces 24 new cases of coronavirus|date=2019-03-12|work=[[Arab News]]|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312161702/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1640286/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n*On 1/ March, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 17 new cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], bringing the total in the Kingdom to 62.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1640766/saudi-arabia|title=17 new cases of coronavirus bring total in Saudi Arabia to 62|date=2019-03-12|work=[[Arab News]]|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313211135/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1640766/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n*On March 13, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 24 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 86.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/13/Saudi-Arabia-detects-24-cases-of-coronavirus-total-rises-to-86.html|title=Saudi Arabia detects 24 cases of coronavirus, total rises to 86|date=2019-03-13|website=Al Arabiya|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314152022/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/13/Saudi-Arabia-detects-24-cases-of-coronavirus-total-rises-to-86.html|archive-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n*On March 14, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 17 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 103.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1641471/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia announces 17 new cases of coronavirus|date=2019-03-14|website=Arab News|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315080538/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1641471/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n*On March 15, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 15 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 118.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2047970#2047970|title=Ministry of Health Reports 15 New Cases of Coronavirus The official Saudi Press Agency|website=www.spa.gov.sa|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n*On March 16, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 15 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 133.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2048363#2048363|title=Ministry of Health Reports 15 New Cases of COVID-19 The official Saudi Press Agency|website=www.spa.gov.sa|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n*On March 17, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 38 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 171.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2048713|website=www.spa.gov.sa|access-date=2020-03-17|title=Ministry of Health Reports 38 New Cases of COVID-19 the official Saudi Press Agency}}</ref>\n* On 18 March, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 67 new cases, 6 of whom are children, bringing the total in the Kingdom to 238.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2049113 |title = Ministry of Health Reports 67 New Cases of COVID-19 the official Saudi Press Agency}}</ref> The ministry also announced the recovery of 6 other cases.\n* On 19 March, Saudi Arabia's health ministry announced 36 new coronavirus cases.\u00a0The ministry said the total number of coronavirus cases in the Kingdom has reached 274.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.arabnews.com/node/1643941/saudi-arabia|title = Saudi Arabia's Health Ministry announced 36 new cases of coronavirus|date = 2020-03-19|access-date = 2020-03-19|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200320021018/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1643941/saudi-arabia|archive-date = 2020-03-20|url-status = live}}</ref> Two more cases have recovered bringing the total number of recovered cases to 8. No deaths have been reported.\n* On 20 March, KSA reported 70 new cases of Novel Coronavirus. The Ministry of Health of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia (KSA) announced the monitoring and registering of 70 new cases of the novel Coronavirus (Covid-19), bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 344.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/20/Saudi-Arabia-confirms-70-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-344.html |title=Saudi Arabia total coronavirus cases at 344, with 70 new cases in 24 hours |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321143221/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/20/Saudi-Arabia-confirms-70-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-344.html |archive-date=2020-03-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a statement announced here at night, the ministry stated that among the new infections (11) were cases coming from: [[Morocco]], [[India]], [[Jordan]], the [[Philippines]], [[United Kingdom|Britain]], the Emirates and [[Switzerland]]. The 11 cases were isolated directly from airports to hospitals, in quarantine (sanitary isolation), proven effective in dealing with the transmission of infection, adding that there is a case of a healthcare practitioner, in Riyadh.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2049792 | title=KSA Reports New 70 Cases of Novel Coronavirus the official Saudi Press Agency}}</ref>\n* On 21 March, Saudi Arabia announces 48 new Coronavirus (COVID-19) cases as total reaches 392.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1644576/saudi-arabia |title=Saudi Arabia announces 48 new coronavirus cases as total reaches 392 |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=2020-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321233251/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1644576/saudi-arabia |archive-date=2020-03-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> Anyone concerned about the virus, or who wants more information about it and precautions that can be taken, can contact the ministry's service center on the toll-free number, 937. Only official sources can be relied on to provide accurate information, the ministry added.\n\n*On 22 March, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 119 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 511.\n*On 23 March, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 51 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 562.\n*On 24 March, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 205 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 767, and it is also reported that a 51-year-old [[Afghan]] national in [[Medina]], [[Saudi Arabia]] was announced as the first casualty from the coronavirus in that country. The Afghan had died on 23 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/afghan-national-dies-covid-19-saudi-arabia|title=Afghan National Dies of COVID-19 in Saudi Arabia|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324161311/https://tolonews.com/health/afghan-national-dies-covid-19-saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/saudi/coronavirus-saudi-arabia-reports-first-death-205-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.1585054457152|title=Coronavirus: Saudi Arabia reports first death, 205 new cases of COVID-19|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324150708/https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/saudi/coronavirus-saudi-arabia-reports-first-death-205-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.1585054457152|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n===Holy sites ===\nOn 27 February 2020, Saudi Arabia announced temporary suspension of entry for individuals wanting to perform the [[Umrah]] pilgrimage in [[Great Mosque of Mecca]] or to visit the [[Prophet's Mosque]] in [[Medina]], as well as tourists. The rule was also extended to visitors traveling from countries where [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] posed a risk.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-china-saudi-idUSKCN20M31T|title=Saudi Arabia temporarily suspends entry of GCC citizens to Mecca and Medina: foreign ministry| first1=Hesham Abdul| last1=Khalek| first2=Chizu| last2=Nomiyama| date=2020-02-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229004835/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-china-saudi-idUSKCN20M31T|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, Saudi Arabia announced further precaution steps regarding the Great Mosque of Mecca and the Prophet's Mosque, which include a temporary daily closure of the Great Mosque for sterilization purposes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637341/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia closes Grand Mosque, Prophet's Mosque between night and morning prayers|last=|first=|date=5 March 2020|website=Arab News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305225452/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637341/saudi-arabia|archive-date=5 March 2020|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Saudi Arabia suspended the holding of daily prayers and the weekly Friday prayers inside and outside the walls of the two mosques in Mecca and Medina\u00a0to limit the spread of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/saudi-arabia-bans-prayers-holy-mosques-coronavirus-fears-200320063001931.html |title=Saudi Arabia bans prayers at mosques over coronavirus fears &#124; Saudi Arabia News &#124; al Jazeera |access-date=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320161749/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/saudi-arabia-bans-prayers-holy-mosques-coronavirus-fears-200320063001931.html |archive-date=2020-03-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Saudi Arabia suspended entry and prayers to the general public at the two Holy Mosques in Mecca and Medina to limit the spread of the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/591064|title=Entry and prayer in courtyards of the Two Holy mosques suspended|date=2020-03-20|website=Saudigazette|language=English|access-date=2020-03-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320190055/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/591064|archive-date=2020-03-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Evacuation===\nOn 2 February, 10 Saudi student evacuees were brought into the country from Wuhan. Their initial negative tests for COVID-19 were announced the following day.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2029780 |title = MOH Confirms that the Results of Preliminary Tests for 10 Saudi Students Coming from Chinese City Wuhan are Negative the official Saudi Press Agency}}</ref> However, they were kept in quarantine for two additional weeks before allowed to return home.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2035314 |title = Ministry of Health Announces Safety of 10 Saudi Students Coming from Wuhan, China the official Saudi Press Agency}}</ref>\n\n===Mobility and Transport===\nOn 6 February, Saudi Arabia had announced a ban on travel to [[China]] on citizens and residents.<ref>[https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2031187 Passports Announces Suspension of Travel to China]</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia suspended direct passenger flights between the Kingdom and China as early as 2 February 2020.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 20 March, The Ministry of Interior suspended domestic flights, trains, buses and taxis for 14 days in a heightened effort to stop the spread of the COVID-19. The new measure will took effect at 6 a.m. ([[Arabian Standard Time|AST]]) on Saturday 2- March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1644101/saudi-arabia |title=Saudi Arabia suspending domestic flights, mass land transport in fight against COVID-19 |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320225358/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1644101/saudi-arabia |archive-date=2020-03-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Customs Control===\nOn 28 February, the Foreign Minister of Saudi Arabia announced the temporary suspension of entry for [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC) citizens to Mecca and Medina. Citizens of the GCC who had been in Saudi Arabia for more than 14 continuous days and didn't show any symptoms of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] would be excluded from this rule.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Lockdown Areas===\nOn 8 March, the Saudi Arabian government announced that it was temporarily halting all transport in and out of [[Qatif]] on its eastern coast, though Qatif residents will be permitted to enter the territory. Cement blocks were reportedly placed as roadblocks on the main road leading to the area. The country's interior ministry stated that all individuals with confirmed cases in the country were from Qatif.<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi locks down Qatif as coronavirus surges in the Gulf |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/saudi-locks-qatif-coronavirus-surges-gulf-200308142809697.html |accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308152713/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/saudi-locks-qatif-coronavirus-surges-gulf-200308142809697.html |archive-date=8 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 30 March, the area of [[Jeddah|Jeddah Governerate]] was subjected to a curfew by the [[Ministry of Interior (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Interior]], with all entries and exits from the city were suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2052560#2052560|title=Ministry of Interior: Curfew in Jeddah Governorate to be effective from 3:00 p.m. on Sunday, and suspension of entry into and exit from it|last=|first=|date=30 March 2020|website=Saudi Press Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other measures===\nOn 7 March, the [[General Sports Authority|Saudi Ministry of Sports]] announced that all sports competitions would be held [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0648\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u0629 \u062a\u064f\u0642\u0631\u0631 \u062a\u0639\u0644\u064a\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0636\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0645\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0631\u064a \u0641\u064a \u062c\u0645\u064a\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u0627\u0641\u0633\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0627\u0641\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0627\u064b \u0645\u0646 \u064a\u0648\u0645 \u063a\u062f\u064d \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0628\u062a |url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=ar&newsid=2043837 |language=arabic |access-date=2020-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313130854/https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=ar&newsid=2043837 |archive-date=2020-03-13 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi Ministry of Sport suspends public attendance at events from Saturday|date=2020-03-06|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637806/saudi-arabia|access-date=2020-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307153958/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637806/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, the Ministry also announced that the 2020 Saudi Olympics Games that was set to be held on 23 March until 1 April was suspended until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0627\u0644\u0644\u062c\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u0638\u0645\u0629 \u062a\u0642\u0631\u0631 \u062a\u0623\u062c\u064a\u0644 #\u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629_\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0628_\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u062d\u062a\u0649 \u0625\u0634\u0639\u0627\u0631 \u0622\u062e\u0631 |url=https://twitter.com/saudiolympic/status/1236719330185957377 |access-date=2020-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308185622/https://twitter.com/saudiolympic/status/1236719330185957377 |archive-date=2020-03-08 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0627\u0644\u0644\u062c\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u0638\u0645\u0629 \u062a\u0639\u0644\u0646 \u062a\u0623\u062c\u064a\u0644 \u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 |date=2020-03-08 |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/sport/saudi-sport/2020/03/08/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%88%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%A4%D8%AC%D9%84-%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9 |language=arabic |access-date=2020-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309182526/https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/sport/saudi-sport/2020/03/08/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%88%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%A4%D8%AC%D9%84-%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9 |archive-date=2020-03-09 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 14 March, the Ministry announced that all sports competitions would be suspended until further notice as well as the closure of all stadiums, sports centers and gyms.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u062a\u0639\u0644\u064a\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0634\u0627\u0637 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0645\u0644\u0643\u0629 \u0648\u0625\u063a\u0644\u0627\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0643\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0627\u0635\u0629 |url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=ru&newsid=2047561}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March, the [[Ministry of Education (Saudi Arabia)|Saudi Ministry of Education]] announced that schools and universities will be closed in Saudi Arabia from Monday to control the spread of coronavirus. The decision covers all educational institutions, including public and private schools, and technical and vocational training institutions.<ref>{{cite news |title=SSaudi Arabia to close schools from Monday over coronavirus |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638606/saudi-arabia |accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=[[Arab News]] |date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310020923/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638606/saudi-arabia |archive-date=10 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, the [[Ministry of Municipal and Rural Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Saudi Ministry of Municipal and Rural Affairs]] announced that they would be closing all amusement parks and entertainment zones in malls as well as that they would be sterilizing and ventilating all restaurants. In addition, the Ministry also announced that they would be banning all social events, including funerals and weddings.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0627\u062a\" \u062a\u0648\u062c\u0651\u0647 \u0628\u0625\u063a\u0644\u0627\u0642 \u0623\u0645\u0627\u0643\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0628 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0646\u0634\u0637\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0641\u064a\u0647\u064a\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062c\u0645\u0651\u0639\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629\u060c \u0648\u062a\u0639\u0642\u064a\u0645 \u0648\u062a\u0647\u0648\u064a\u0629 \u200f\u0623\u0645\u0627\u0643\u0646 \u062a\u0642\u062f\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0637\u0639\u0645\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0634\u0631\u0648\u0628\u0627\u062a |url=https://www.momra.gov.sa/MediaCenter/News/Newsdetails.aspx?ID=1687&type=News |language=Arabic}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, the Ministry announced the closure of all shopping malls, restaurants, coffee shops, and public parks with the exception of pharmacies and supermarkets.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u062a\u063a\u0644\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0643\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0637\u0627\u0639\u0645 \u0644\u0644\u062d\u062f \u0645\u0646 \u0643\u0648\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627|date=2020-03-15|url=https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/saudi-today/2020/03/15/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D8%BA%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AC%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316163606/https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/saudi-today/2020/03/15/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D8%BA%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AC%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA|archive-date=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1643431/saudi-arabia%20%2818%20March%2C%202020%29|title=Saudi Health Ministry announces 67 new cases of coronavirus|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:2020 in Saudi Arabia|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Saudi Arabia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Saudi Arabia}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saudi Arabia\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| first_case      = [[Qatif]]\n| arrival_date    = 2 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=02|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]] via [[Iran]], [[Bahrain]], [[Oman]], [[Egypt]], [[France]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| recovery_cases  = 328<ref name=\"sg-24march\"/>\n| deaths          = 21<ref name=\"sg-24march\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 1,536<ref name=\"sg-24march\">{{cite news|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/591187/SAUDI-ARABIA/Saudi-Arabia-confirms-first-corona-death-205-new-cases-detected|title=Saudi Arabia confirms first corona death, 205 new cases detected|work=Saudi Gazette|date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324164533/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/591187/SAUDI-ARABIA/Saudi-Arabia-confirms-first-corona-death-205-new-cases-detected|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = https://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/events/covid-19/Pages/2020.aspx|website\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 Coronavirus Pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Saudi Arabia]] on March 2, 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{further|Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Saudi Arabia medical cases chart}}\n\n===March 2020===\n*On 2 March 2020, [[Saudi Arabia]] confirmed its first case, a Saudi national returning from [[Iran]] via [[Bahrain]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1635781/saudi-arabia |title=Saudi Arabia announces first case of coronavirus |date=2020-03-02 |access-date=2 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302170439/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1635781/saudi-arabia |archive-date=2 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n*On 4 March, Saudi Arabia reported a second coronavirus case, a companion of the first, who crossed the [[King_Fahd_Causeway|causeway]] from Bahrain without disclosing that he had visited Iran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1636926/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia detects second coronavirus case|website=Arab News|date=2020-03-04|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305103618/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1636926/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*On 5 March, Saudi Arabia's [[Ministry of Health (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Health]] announced three new cases of coronavirus; two of which are a couple who traveled from Iran via [[Kuwait]] and one, another companion of the first and second cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637311/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia announces three more cases of coronavirus|website=Arab News|date=2020-03-05|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307035753/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637311/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*On 6 March, the Ministry of Health announced a further two cases, both being female. One was from Iran via Bahrain and the other was from [[Najaf]], [[Iraq]] through the [[UAE|Emirates]]. Both did not tell the authorities where they had been and thus, were let in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638111/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia announces 2 new cases of coronavirus coming from Iran, Iraq|website=Arab News|date=2020-03-07|access-date=2020-03-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308152845/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638111/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*On 8 March, the Ministry of Health announced 4 more cases. Three of the four patients are citizens who were in contact with previous infected cases arriving from Iran, and the fourth case is a citizen arriving from Iran via the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638471/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia announces 4 new coronavirus cases|website=Arab News|date=2020-03-08|access-date=2020-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308203441/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638471/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*On 9 March, Saudi authorities announced the discovery of four more new coronavirus cases. The new cases include a Saudi national, two Bahrainis, and an American. All the new cases have been quarantined in [[Qatif]] and [[Riyadh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/590618|title=Saudi Arabia discovers 4 more virus cases, suspends travel to 9 countries|website=Arab News|date=2020-03-09|access-date=2020-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310202407/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/590618|archive-date=2020-03-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On 10 March, the Ministry of Health announced 5 more cases, bringing the total to 20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arab.news/cdzr4|title=Saudi health ministry announces five new coronavirus cases|date=2020-03-10|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n*On 11 March, the Ministry of Health announced 1 more case, an Egyptian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/coronavirus/2020/03/11/Saudi-Arabia-reports-new-coronavirus-case-in-Egyptian-citizen-total-up-to-21.html|title=SSaudi Arabia reports new coronavirus case in Egyptian traveler, total up to 21|date=2020-03-11|website=alarabiya|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321052007/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/coronavirus/2020/03/11/Saudi-Arabia-reports-new-coronavirus-case-in-Egyptian-citizen-total-up-to-21.html|archive-date=2020-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, the Ministry further announced 24 more cases, 21 of which are Egyptians who had been in contact with a person who previously tested positive, taking the country's total to 45.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1640286/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia announces 24 new cases of coronavirus|date=2019-03-12|work=[[Arab News]]|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312161702/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1640286/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n*On 1/ March, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 17 new cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], bringing the total in the Kingdom to 62.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1640766/saudi-arabia|title=17 new cases of coronavirus bring total in Saudi Arabia to 62|date=2019-03-12|work=[[Arab News]]|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313211135/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1640766/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n*On March 13, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 24 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 86.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/13/Saudi-Arabia-detects-24-cases-of-coronavirus-total-rises-to-86.html|title=Saudi Arabia detects 24 cases of coronavirus, total rises to 86|date=2019-03-13|website=Al Arabiya|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314152022/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/13/Saudi-Arabia-detects-24-cases-of-coronavirus-total-rises-to-86.html|archive-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n*On March 14, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 17 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 103.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1641471/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia announces 17 new cases of coronavirus|date=2019-03-14|website=Arab News|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315080538/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1641471/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n*On March 15, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 15 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 118.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2047970#2047970|title=Ministry of Health Reports 15 New Cases of Coronavirus The official Saudi Press Agency|website=www.spa.gov.sa|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n*On March 16, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 15 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 133.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2048363#2048363|title=Ministry of Health Reports 15 New Cases of COVID-19 The official Saudi Press Agency|website=www.spa.gov.sa|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n*On March 17, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 38 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 171.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2048713|website=www.spa.gov.sa|access-date=2020-03-17|title=Ministry of Health Reports 38 New Cases of COVID-19 the official Saudi Press Agency}}</ref>\n* On 18 March, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 67 new cases, 6 of whom are children, bringing the total in the Kingdom to 238.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2049113 |title = Ministry of Health Reports 67 New Cases of COVID-19 the official Saudi Press Agency}}</ref> The ministry also announced the recovery of 6 other cases.\n* On 19 March, Saudi Arabia's health ministry announced 36 new coronavirus cases.\u00a0The ministry said the total number of coronavirus cases in the Kingdom has reached 274.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.arabnews.com/node/1643941/saudi-arabia|title = Saudi Arabia's Health Ministry announced 36 new cases of coronavirus|date = 2020-03-19|access-date = 2020-03-19|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200320021018/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1643941/saudi-arabia|archive-date = 2020-03-20|url-status = live}}</ref> Two more cases have recovered bringing the total number of recovered cases to 8. No deaths have been reported.\n* On 20 March, KSA reported 70 new cases of Novel Coronavirus. The Ministry of Health of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia (KSA) announced the monitoring and registering of 70 new cases of the novel Coronavirus (Covid-19), bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 344.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/20/Saudi-Arabia-confirms-70-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-344.html |title=Saudi Arabia total coronavirus cases at 344, with 70 new cases in 24 hours |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321143221/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/20/Saudi-Arabia-confirms-70-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-344.html |archive-date=2020-03-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a statement announced here at night, the ministry stated that among the new infections (11) were cases coming from: [[Morocco]], [[India]], [[Jordan]], the [[Philippines]], [[United Kingdom|Britain]], the Emirates and [[Switzerland]]. The 11 cases were isolated directly from airports to hospitals, in quarantine (sanitary isolation), proven effective in dealing with the transmission of infection, adding that there is a case of a healthcare practitioner, in Riyadh.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2049792 | title=KSA Reports New 70 Cases of Novel Coronavirus the official Saudi Press Agency}}</ref>\n* On 21 March, Saudi Arabia announces 48 new Coronavirus (COVID-19) cases as total reaches 392.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1644576/saudi-arabia |title=Saudi Arabia announces 48 new coronavirus cases as total reaches 392 |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=2020-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321233251/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1644576/saudi-arabia |archive-date=2020-03-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> Anyone concerned about the virus, or who wants more information about it and precautions that can be taken, can contact the ministry's service center on the toll-free number, 937. Only official sources can be relied on to provide accurate information, the ministry added.\n\n*On 22 March, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 119 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 511.\n*On 23 March, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 51 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 562.\n*On 24 March, the Saudi Ministry of Health announced 205 new cases, bringing the total in Saudi Arabia to 767, and it is also reported that a 51-year-old [[Afghan]] national in [[Medina]], [[Saudi Arabia]] was announced as the first casualty from the coronavirus in that country. The Afghan had died on 23 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tolonews.com/health/afghan-national-dies-covid-19-saudi-arabia|title=Afghan National Dies of COVID-19 in Saudi Arabia|website=TOLOnews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324161311/https://tolonews.com/health/afghan-national-dies-covid-19-saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/saudi/coronavirus-saudi-arabia-reports-first-death-205-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.1585054457152|title=Coronavirus: Saudi Arabia reports first death, 205 new cases of COVID-19|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324150708/https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/saudi/coronavirus-saudi-arabia-reports-first-death-205-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.1585054457152|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n===Holy sites ===\nOn 27 February 2020, Saudi Arabia announced temporary suspension of entry for individuals wanting to perform the [[Umrah]] pilgrimage in [[Great Mosque of Mecca]] or to visit the [[Prophet's Mosque]] in [[Medina]], as well as tourists. The rule was also extended to visitors traveling from countries where [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] posed a risk.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-china-saudi-idUSKCN20M31T|title=Saudi Arabia temporarily suspends entry of GCC citizens to Mecca and Medina: foreign ministry| first1=Hesham Abdul| last1=Khalek| first2=Chizu| last2=Nomiyama| date=2020-02-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229004835/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-china-saudi-idUSKCN20M31T|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, Saudi Arabia announced further precaution steps regarding the Great Mosque of Mecca and the Prophet's Mosque, which include a temporary daily closure of the Great Mosque for sterilization purposes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637341/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia closes Grand Mosque, Prophet's Mosque between night and morning prayers|last=|first=|date=5 March 2020|website=Arab News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305225452/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637341/saudi-arabia|archive-date=5 March 2020|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Saudi Arabia suspended the holding of daily prayers and the weekly Friday prayers inside and outside the walls of the two mosques in Mecca and Medina\u00a0to limit the spread of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/saudi-arabia-bans-prayers-holy-mosques-coronavirus-fears-200320063001931.html |title=Saudi Arabia bans prayers at mosques over coronavirus fears &#124; Saudi Arabia News &#124; al Jazeera |access-date=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320161749/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/saudi-arabia-bans-prayers-holy-mosques-coronavirus-fears-200320063001931.html |archive-date=2020-03-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Saudi Arabia suspended entry and prayers to the general public at the two Holy Mosques in Mecca and Medina to limit the spread of the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/591064|title=Entry and prayer in courtyards of the Two Holy mosques suspended|date=2020-03-20|website=Saudigazette|language=English|access-date=2020-03-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320190055/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/591064|archive-date=2020-03-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Evacuation===\nOn 2 February, 10 Saudi student evacuees were brought into the country from Wuhan. Their initial negative tests for COVID-19 were announced the following day.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2029780 |title = MOH Confirms that the Results of Preliminary Tests for 10 Saudi Students Coming from Chinese City Wuhan are Negative the official Saudi Press Agency}}</ref> However, they were kept in quarantine for two additional weeks before allowed to return home.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2035314 |title = Ministry of Health Announces Safety of 10 Saudi Students Coming from Wuhan, China the official Saudi Press Agency}}</ref>\n\n===Mobility and Transport===\nOn 6 February, Saudi Arabia had announced a ban on travel to [[China]] on citizens and residents.<ref>[https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2031187 Passports Announces Suspension of Travel to China]</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia suspended direct passenger flights between the Kingdom and China as early as 2 February 2020.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 20 March, The Ministry of Interior suspended domestic flights, trains, buses and taxis for 14 days in a heightened effort to stop the spread of the COVID-19. The new measure will took effect at 6 a.m. ([[Arabian Standard Time|AST]]) on Saturday 2- March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1644101/saudi-arabia |title=Saudi Arabia suspending domestic flights, mass land transport in fight against COVID-19 |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320225358/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1644101/saudi-arabia |archive-date=2020-03-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Customs Control===\nOn 28 February, the Foreign Minister of Saudi Arabia announced the temporary suspension of entry for [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC) citizens to Mecca and Medina. Citizens of the GCC who had been in Saudi Arabia for more than 14 continuous days and didn't show any symptoms of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] would be excluded from this rule.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Lockdown Areas===\nOn 8 March, the Saudi Arabian government announced that it was temporarily halting all transport in and out of [[Qatif]] on its eastern coast, though Qatif residents will be permitted to enter the territory. Cement blocks were reportedly placed as roadblocks on the main road leading to the area. The country's interior ministry stated that all individuals with confirmed cases in the country were from Qatif.<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi locks down Qatif as coronavirus surges in the Gulf |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/saudi-locks-qatif-coronavirus-surges-gulf-200308142809697.html |accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308152713/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/saudi-locks-qatif-coronavirus-surges-gulf-200308142809697.html |archive-date=8 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 30 March, the area of [[Jeddah|Jeddah Governerate]] was subjected to a curfew by the [[Ministry of Interior (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Interior]], with all entries and exits from the city were suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=en&newsid=2052560#2052560|title=Ministry of Interior: Curfew in Jeddah Governorate to be effective from 3:00 p.m. on Sunday, and suspension of entry into and exit from it|last=|first=|date=30 March 2020|website=Saudi Press Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other measures===\nOn 7 March, the [[General Sports Authority|Saudi Ministry of Sports]] announced that all sports competitions would be held [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0648\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u0629 \u062a\u064f\u0642\u0631\u0631 \u062a\u0639\u0644\u064a\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0636\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0645\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0631\u064a \u0641\u064a \u062c\u0645\u064a\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u0627\u0641\u0633\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0627\u0641\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0627\u064b \u0645\u0646 \u064a\u0648\u0645 \u063a\u062f\u064d \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0628\u062a |url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=ar&newsid=2043837 |language=arabic |access-date=2020-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313130854/https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewfullstory.php?lang=ar&newsid=2043837 |archive-date=2020-03-13 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi Ministry of Sport suspends public attendance at events from Saturday|date=2020-03-06|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637806/saudi-arabia|access-date=2020-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307153958/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1637806/saudi-arabia|archive-date=2020-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, the Ministry also announced that the 2020 Saudi Olympics Games that was set to be held on 23 March until 1 April was suspended until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0627\u0644\u0644\u062c\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u0638\u0645\u0629 \u062a\u0642\u0631\u0631 \u062a\u0623\u062c\u064a\u0644 #\u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629_\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0628_\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u062d\u062a\u0649 \u0625\u0634\u0639\u0627\u0631 \u0622\u062e\u0631 |url=https://twitter.com/saudiolympic/status/1236719330185957377 |access-date=2020-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308185622/https://twitter.com/saudiolympic/status/1236719330185957377 |archive-date=2020-03-08 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0627\u0644\u0644\u062c\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u0638\u0645\u0629 \u062a\u0639\u0644\u0646 \u062a\u0623\u062c\u064a\u0644 \u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 |date=2020-03-08 |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/sport/saudi-sport/2020/03/08/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%88%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%A4%D8%AC%D9%84-%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9 |language=arabic |access-date=2020-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309182526/https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/sport/saudi-sport/2020/03/08/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%88%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%A4%D8%AC%D9%84-%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9 |archive-date=2020-03-09 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 14 March, the Ministry announced that all sports competitions would be suspended until further notice as well as the closure of all stadiums, sports centers and gyms.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u062a\u0639\u0644\u064a\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0634\u0627\u0637 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0645\u0644\u0643\u0629 \u0648\u0625\u063a\u0644\u0627\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0643\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0627\u0635\u0629 |url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=ru&newsid=2047561}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March, the [[Ministry of Education (Saudi Arabia)|Saudi Ministry of Education]] announced that schools and universities will be closed in Saudi Arabia from Monday to control the spread of coronavirus. The decision covers all educational institutions, including public and private schools, and technical and vocational training institutions.<ref>{{cite news |title=SSaudi Arabia to close schools from Monday over coronavirus |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638606/saudi-arabia |accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=[[Arab News]] |date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310020923/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1638606/saudi-arabia |archive-date=10 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, the [[Ministry of Municipal and Rural Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Saudi Ministry of Municipal and Rural Affairs]] announced that they would be closing all amusement parks and entertainment zones in malls as well as that they would be sterilizing and ventilating all restaurants. In addition, the Ministry also announced that they would be banning all social events, including funerals and weddings.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0627\u062a\" \u062a\u0648\u062c\u0651\u0647 \u0628\u0625\u063a\u0644\u0627\u0642 \u0623\u0645\u0627\u0643\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0628 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0646\u0634\u0637\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0641\u064a\u0647\u064a\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062c\u0645\u0651\u0639\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629\u060c \u0648\u062a\u0639\u0642\u064a\u0645 \u0648\u062a\u0647\u0648\u064a\u0629 \u200f\u0623\u0645\u0627\u0643\u0646 \u062a\u0642\u062f\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0637\u0639\u0645\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0634\u0631\u0648\u0628\u0627\u062a |url=https://www.momra.gov.sa/MediaCenter/News/Newsdetails.aspx?ID=1687&type=News |language=Arabic}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, the Ministry announced the closure of all shopping malls, restaurants, coffee shops, and public parks with the exception of pharmacies and supermarkets.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u062a\u063a\u0644\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0643\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0637\u0627\u0639\u0645 \u0644\u0644\u062d\u062f \u0645\u0646 \u0643\u0648\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627|date=2020-03-15|url=https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/saudi-today/2020/03/15/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D8%BA%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AC%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316163606/https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/saudi-today/2020/03/15/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D8%BA%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AC%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AC%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AA|archive-date=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1643431/saudi-arabia%20%2818%20March%2C%202020%29|title=Saudi Health Ministry announces 67 new cases of coronavirus|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:2020 in Saudi Arabia|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Saudi Arabia]]\n", "name_user": "KH561", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(New 165 Cases)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Saudi_Arabia"}
{"title_page": "Jim Jordan (American politician)", "text_new": "{{For|other people named Jim Jordan or James Jordan|James Jordan (disambiguation){{!}}James Jordan}}\n{{short description|U.S. Representative from Ohio}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Jim Jordan\n|image         = Jim Jordan official photo, 114th Congress.jpg\n|office        = [[Ranking Member]] of the <br>[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|House Judiciary Committee]]\n|term_start    = March 12, 2020\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Doug Collins (politician)|Doug Collins]]\n|successor     = \n|office1       = [[Ranking Member]] of the <br>[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform|House Oversight Committee]]\n|term_start1   = January 3, 2019 \n|term_end1     = March 12, 2020\n|predecessor1  = [[Elijah Cummings]]\n|successor1    = [[Mark Meadows (North Carolina politician)|Mark Meadows]]\n|state2        = [[Ohio]]\n|district2     = {{ushr|OH|4|4th}}\n|term_start2   = January 3, 2007\n|term_end2     = \n|predecessor2  = [[Mike Oxley]]\n|successor2    = \n|state_senate3 = Ohio\n|district3     = 12th\n|term_start3   = January 3, 2001\n|term_end3     = December 31, 2006\n|predecessor3  = [[Robert R. Cupp]]\n|successor3    = [[Keith Faber]]\n|state_house4  = Ohio\n|district4     = 85th\n|term_start4   = January 3, 1995\n|term_end4     = December 31, 2000\n|predecessor4  = [[Jim Davis (Ohio politician)|Jim Davis]]\n|successor4    = [[Derrick Seaver]]\n|birth_name    = James Daniel Jordan\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1964|2|17}}\n|birth_place   = [[Urbana, Ohio]], U.S.\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse        = Polly Jordan\n|children      = 4\n|education     = [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Ohio State University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])<br>[[Capital University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''James Daniel Jordan''' (born February 17, 1964) is an American politician, former collegiate [[freestyle wrestling|wrestler]], and former collegiate wrestling coach. He has served as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. representative]] for {{ushr|OH|4}} since 2007. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party,]] Jordan was the ranking member of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|House Oversight Committee]] from 2019 to 2020. In February 2020, he left that committee to become the ranking member of the [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary]].\n\nJordan is a founding member of the [[Freedom Caucus]], which he chaired from its establishment in 2015 until 2017. His district stretches from Lake Erie to just below [[Urbana, Ohio|Urbana]] in the north-central and western portions of the state and includes [[Lima, Ohio|Lima]], [[Marion, Ohio|Marion]], [[Tiffin, Ohio|Tiffin]], [[Urbana, Ohio|Urbana]], and [[Elyria, Ohio|Elyria]].\n\n==Early life, education and early career==\nJordan was born and raised in [[Champaign County, Ohio]]. He attended and wrestled for [[Graham High School (St. Paris, Ohio)|Graham High School]], graduating in 1982. He won state championships all four years he was in high school and compiled a 156\u201328\u20131 win-loss record.  He then enrolled at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] where he became a two-time [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] wrestling champion. Jordan won the 1985 and 1986 NCAA championship matches in the 134-pound weight class.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nwhof.org/NCAA-Brackets/PDF/NCAA%201985.pdf|title=55th NCAA Wrestling Tournament 1985 - 3/14/1985 to 3/16/1985 at Oklahoma City|last=Jordan|first=Jim|date=March 16, 1985 |website=nwhof.org |access-date=October 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nwhof.org/stillwater/hall-of-fame/#type=hof&honoree=8647|title=Wrestling Hall of Fame {{!}} National Wrestling Hall of Fame|language=en-US|access-date=October 31, 2019}}</ref> He graduated with a bachelor's degree in economics in 1986. He lost the 57\u201362&nbsp;kg featherweight semi-final match at the 1988 US Olympic wrestling trials and did not make the Olympic team.\n\nJordan earned a master's degree in education from [[Ohio State University]] in [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]] and obtained a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from Ohio's [[Capital University Law School]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abovethelaw.com/schools/capital-university-law-school/|title=Capital University Law School|website=Above the Law|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> in 2001. In a 2018 interview Jordan said \"Never took the bar exam, so don't, like - I'm not - I'm just a wannabe.\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/03/20/595145615/questions-mount-about-if-and-when-robert-mueller-will-interview-trump|title=Questions Mount About If And When Robert Mueller Will Interview Trump|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\nJordan was an assistant wrestling coach with Ohio State University's (OSU) wrestling program from 1987 to 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20180703/lawyers-for-ohio-state-contradict-jim-jordans-claim-hes-not-been-contacted|title=Lawyers for Ohio State contradict Jim Jordan's claim he's not been contacted|last=Smola|first=Jennifer|website=The Columbus Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thedailybanter.com/2018/07/03/breaking-ohio-representative-jim-jordan-sat-on-sexual-abuse-allegations-at-ohio-state-former-athletes-say/|title=BREAKING: Ohio Representative Jim Jordan Sat on Sexual Abuse Allegations at Ohio State, Former Athletes Say|last=Fassler|first=Jeremy|website=The Daily Banter|language=en-us|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Ohio General Assembly===\nJordan was elected to the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] in November 1994 and represented the 85th Ohio House district for three terms.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn 2000, Jordan defeated independent candidate Jack Kaffenberger to win a seat in the [[Ohio Senate]] with 88% of the vote. In 2004, Jordan defeated Kaffenberger again, this time with 79% of the vote.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===U.S. House of Representatives===\nJordan represents Western [[Ohio's 4th congressional district|Ohio's 4th Congressional District]]. The district has been redrawn over time to minimize urban area and increase the rural area; it is gerrymandered to avoid having Toledo, Columbus or Cleveland (or their respective suburbs) in the district which stretches from [[Lake Erie]] nearly to [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]]'''.''' A three-judge federal panel unanimously ruled in May 2019 that Ohio's congressional district map is unconstitutional due to partisan gerrymandering and ordered the state to create a new map in time for the 2020 election. As of May 2019, the issue remained unresolved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/open/2019/05/federal-judges-toss-out-ohios-congressional-map-as-illegal-gerrymander.html|title=Federal judges toss out Ohio's congressional map as illegal gerrymander|last=Exner|first=Rich|date=2019-05-03|website=cleveland|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wksu.org/post/how-did-ohios-most-liberal-city-end-its-most-conservative-congressman|title=How Did Ohio&#039;s Most Liberal City End Up With Its Most Conservative Congressman?|last=Schultze|first=M. L.|website=www.wksu.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> \n[[File:Jordan and Meadows.jpg|alt=|thumb|Jordan and Meadows discussing issues in 2017]]\nJordan won the Republican primary for the 4th district in 2006 after 26-year incumbent [[Mike Oxley]] announced his retirement. Jordan defeated Democrat Rick Siferd in the general election with 60 percent of the votes.<ref name=\"Jim Jordan Ohio\">{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Jim_Jordan_(Ohio)|title=Jim Jordan (Ohio)|website=Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\nJordan was reelected in 2008, defeating Democrat Mike Carroll with 65 percent of the votes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/2008ElectionResults/congress110408.aspx |title=U.S. Congress: November 4, 2008 |publisher=Sos.state.oh.us |date=November 4, 2008 |accessdate=August 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811034938/http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/2008ElectionResults/congress110408.aspx |archivedate=August 11, 2010  }}</ref>\n\nJordan was reelected in 2010, defeating Democrat Doug Litt and Libertarian Donald Kissick with 71 percent of the votes.<ref name=\"Jim Jordan Ohio\"/>\n\nJordan chaired the [[Republican Study Committee]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref> during the 112th Congress<ref>{{cite web|author=Sabrina Eaton/The Plain Dealer |url=http://www.cleveland.com/open/index.ssf/2010/12/rep_jim_jordan_selected_to_cha.html |title=Rep. Jim Jordan selected to chair Republican Study Committee |publisher=cleveland.com |date=December 8, 2010 |accessdate=July 17, 2011}}</ref> while turning down a position on the [[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Appropriations Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1110/45250.html |title=Appropriations panel loses its luster \u2013 Simmi Aujla and Richard E. Cohen |publisher=Politico.Com |date= |accessdate=July 17, 2011}}</ref> During the U.S. government shutdown of 2013, he was considered{{by whom|date=February 2020}} the most powerful member of the committee.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/inside-the-republican-suicide-machine-20131009|title=Tea Party Politics: A Look Inside the Republican Suicide Machine|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref> That group was the primary proponent and executor of the Republican Congressional strategy to force a government shutdown, in order to force changes in the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], also known as Obamacare.<ref name=\"rollingstone.com\"/>\n\nJordan received a vote for speaker of the [[113th United States Congress|113th Congress]] from a fellow right-wing conservative, [[Tea Party Caucus]] chairman [[Tim Huelskamp]] of [[Kansas]]. Jordan received two votes for speaker during the [[114th United States Congress|114th Congress]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2015/01/06/first-congress-boehner-election/21330229/|title=Boehner re-elected as speaker despite GOP dissenters|first=Susan|last=Davis|newspaper=USA Today|date=January 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2018, Jordan announced his bid for [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|house speaker]] following resignation of [[Paul Ryan]],<ref name=CNN>[https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/26/politics/jim-jordan-running-for-house-speaker/index.html Conservative Ohio Rep. Jim Jordan to run for House speaker], ''[[CNN]]'', Sunlen Serfaty and Lauren Fox, July 26, 2018. Retrieved July 27, 2018.</ref> but lost to [[Kevin McCarthy (California politician)|Kevin McCarthy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/11/14/18091966/kevin-mccarthy-minority-leader-house-jim-jordan|title=Kevin McCarthy finally gets to be the top House Republican \u2014 but in the minority|first=Tara|last=Golshan|date=November 14, 2018|website=Vox}}</ref> His campaign ended when [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] took the majority in the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"CNN\" /> Subsequently, Jordan campaigned for [[House Minority Leader|house minority leader]]. Former Ohio state representative Capri Cafar said that Jordan, \"...is someone who has built a reputation as an attack dog, someone who is media savvy, someone who is a stalwart supporter of the president and who has the skill necessary to take the lead for the GOP.\"<ref name=CSM/> He lost his bid to California Republican McCarthy in a 159\u201343 vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/11/14/667488296/house-republicans-to-choose-leaders-after-midterm-defeat|title=After Midterm Losses, House Republicans Elect McCarthy As Top Leader|last1=Snell|first1=Kelsey|date=November 14, 2018|accessdate=28 February 2019|agency=NPR}}</ref>\n\nJordan was the ranking member of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|House Oversight Committee]] from 2019 to 2020. In February 2020, Jordan left his position on the Committee on Oversight and Government Reform and replaced [[Doug Collins (politician)|Doug Collins]] on the [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary]]. Collins was required to step down from the committee post after launching his [[2020 United States Senate special election in Georgia|2020 Senate bid]]. Jordan was replaced on the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform by [[Mark Meadows (North Carolina politician)|Mark Meadows]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/481933-jim-jordan-selected-to-replace-doug-collins-on-judiciary-committee|title=House Republicans move Jordan to Judiciary, Meadows to Oversight|date=2020-02-06|last=Beavers|first=Olivia|last2=Brufke|first2=Juliegrace|website=The Hill|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref><ref>https://www.foxnews.com/politics/jim-jordan-ranking-member-house-judiciary-committee</ref>\n[[File:Jim Jordan speaks during Trump Impeachment protest.jpg|alt=|thumb|Jordan addresses the media in November 2019 after the Republican \"sit-in\" that delayed an impeachment deposition.]]\n\n====Freedom Caucus====\nDuring the 114th Congress, Jordan and eight other members of Congress founded the House [[Freedom Caucus]], a bloc of conservatives working to \"to advance an agenda of limited constitutional government\" in Congress.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/open/index.ssf/2015/01/rep_jim_jordan_will_head_new_g.html|title=Rep. Jim Jordan to co-found new GOP \"House Freedom Caucus\"|first=Sabrina|last=Eaton|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=January 26, 2015}}</ref> He served as the group's first chairman.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/open/index.ssf/2015/02/its_official_rep_jim_jordan_no.html|title=It's official: Rep. Jim Jordan now chairs the House Freedom Caucus|first=Sabrina|last=Eaton|newspaper=Cleveland Plain Dealer|date=February 11, 2015|access-date=March 12, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216113136/https://www.cleveland.com/open/index.ssf/2015/02/its_official_rep_jim_jordan_no.html|archive-date=February 16, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> The caucus was ultimately credited with pushing Speaker [[John Boehner]] into retirement.<ref name=CSM/>\n\n====Committee assignments====\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet|Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet]]\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice|Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]''' (ranking member)\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Health Care, Benefits and Administrative Rules|Subcommittee on Health Care, Benefits, and Administrative Rules]]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Government Operations|Subcommittee on Government Operations]]\n* [[House Select Committee on the Events Surrounding the 2012 Terrorist Attack in Benghazi]]\n* '''[[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|Committee on Intelligence]] (Temporary)'''\n\n====Caucus memberships====\n* [[Freedom Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=French|first1=Lauren|title=9 Republicans launch House Freedom Caucus|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/01/house-freedom-caucus-conservative-legislation-114593|website=Politico|access-date=December 26, 2016|date=January 26, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Congressional Constitution Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalconstitutioncaucus-garrett.house.gov/about-us/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Constitution Caucus|date=|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=June 27, 2018}}</ref> \n*[[U.S.-Japan Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://usjapancaucus-castro.house.gov/members|format=| publisher=U.S. - Japan Caucus |date=|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Legislation====\nOn May 2, 2014, Jordan introduced [[Calling on Attorney General Eric H. Holder, Jr., to appoint a special counsel to investigate the targeting of conservative nonprofit groups by the Internal Revenue Service (H.Res. 565; 113th Congress)|House Resolution 565]] entitled [[Calling on Attorney General Eric H. Holder, Jr., to appoint a special counsel to investigate the targeting of conservative nonprofit groups by the Internal Revenue Service (H.Res. 565; 113th Congress)|Calling on Attorney General Eric H. Holder, Jr., to appoint a special counsel to investigate the targeting of conservative nonprofit groups by the Internal Revenue Service]]  that passed on May 7, 2014.<ref name=565allactions>{{cite web|title=H.Res. 565 \u2013 All Actions|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-resolution/565/all-actions/|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Jordan criticized the newly introduced [[American Health Care Act]], the Republican replacement bill for the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], calling it an unacceptable form of \"Obamacare Lite.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/13/the-associated-press-republicans-brace-for-downbeat-cbo-analysis-of-health-bill.html|title=Republicans brace for downbeat CBO analysis of health bill|last=Yen|first=Hope|date=March 13, 2017|website=CNBC|access-date=March 13, 2017}}</ref> On May 4, 2017, he voted to pass a revised version of the legislation.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/05/04/health-care-vote-puts-pressure-dozens-vulnerable-gop-reps/101297824/|title=Health care vote puts pressure on dozens of vulnerable GOP reps|work=USA Today|access-date=May 4, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn June 13, 2018, Jordan and [[Mark Meadows (North Carolina politician)|Mark Meadows]] (R-NC) filed a resolution to compel the Department of Justice to provide certain documents to Congress relating to the ongoing congressional investigations of interference by Russia in the 2016 election.  The resolution asserted that the DOJ was stonewalling congressional oversight and sought to give the DOJ seven days from its enactment to turn over documents related to both Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein's appointment of Special Counsel Robert Mueller as well as various decisions made by the FBI during the 2016 presidential election. Jordan issued a press release that stated: <blockquote>This resolution gives the DOJ seven days to turn over the documents that they owe Congress. Rod Rosenstein threatened congressional staff. When the bully picks on your little brother, you have to respond. It's time for House Leadership to stand up and pass this resolution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jordan.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=398154|title=Congressmen Jordan and Meadows File Resolution Telling Department of Justice to Turn Over Documents|date=2018-06-13|website=U.S. Congressman Jim Jordan|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn July 25, 2018, Jordan and Mark Meadows introduced Articles of Impeachment against Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]] who they accused of \"intentionally withholding embarrassing documents and information, knowingly hiding material investigative information from Congress, various abuses of the FISA process, and failure to comply with congressional subpoenas, among others.  Jordan stated that impeachment was necessary because: <blockquote>The DOJ is keeping information from Congress. Enough is enough. It's time to hold Mr. Rosenstein accountable for blocking Congress\u2019s constitutional oversight role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jordan.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=398157|title=Rep. Jordan, Rep. Meadows Introduce Articles of Impeachment Against Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein|date=2018-07-25|website=U.S. Congressman Jim Jordan|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2A6X1B8|title=House conservatives move to impeach Rosenstein|last=Cheney|first=Kyle|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nJordan and [[Warren Davidson]] (R., Ohio) were the only members of the Ohio congressional delegation that voted in October 2019 against a bipartisan resolution that passed the House 354\u201360 condemning President [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] unilateral withdrawal of U.S. military forces from Syria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5702534/house-condemns-syria-withdrawal/|title=House Approves Bipartisan Measure Condemning Trump's Withdrawal of U.S. Troops in Syria|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref><ref>[https://www.toledoblade.com/news/nation/2019/10/17/sortman-Syria-withdrawal-send-the-wrong-message-to-us-allies/stories/20191017106 Portman: Syria withdrawal sends the wrong message to U.S. allies], ''[[Toledo Blade]]'', Liz Skalka, Retrieved October 24, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Political positions===\nAccording to ''[[Dayton Daily News|The Dayton Daily News]]'', Jordan \"is known for being one of Congress' most conservative members.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/local/who-rep-jim-jordan-favorite-liberal-the-answer-might-surprise-you/lorSabCH8mvczy7dhdeniK/|title=Who is Rep. Jim Jordan's favorite liberal? The answer might surprise you.|work=daytondailynews|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>\n\nIn Congress, Jordan is among the most conservative Republicans, earning a perfect score from the [[American Conservative Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acuratings.org/2008all.htm#OH|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090324015608/http://www.acuratings.org/2008all.htm#OH|title=2008 Votes By State Delegation|archivedate=March 24, 2009|work=archive.org|accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref> He has voted consistently for [[anti-abortion]] legislation and was endorsed by Ohio Right to Life in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ohio Right to Life|url=http://www.ohiovotesforlife.org/endorsements/|publisher=Ohiovotesforlife.org|accessdate=November 9, 2012}}</ref> During the [[112th Congress]], he was one of 40 \"staunch\" members of the [[Republican Study Committee]] who frequently voted against Republican party leadership and vocally expressed displeasure with House bills.<ref name=\"rsc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/17/us/politics/house-freshmen-not-as-defiant-as-their-reputation-suggests.html?_r=1&hp|title=G.O.P. Freshmen Not as Defiant as Reputation Suggests|first=Jennifer|last=Steinhauer|newspaper=New York Times|date=March 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nJordan was a leading critic of President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Home Affordable Modification Program|Home Affordable Modification Program (HAMP)]] program, advocating for its shutdown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704075604575356663725805580 |title=Cleaning Up the Mortgage Mess |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=August 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nJordan has supported the continued production and upgrades of [[M1 Abrams]] tanks in his district.<ref name='Lardner01'>{{cite news | first = Richard | last = Lardner |title=Army says no to more tanks, but Congress insists |date=April 28, 2013 |url=https://news.yahoo.com/army-says-no-more-tanks-congress-insists-115422396.html |work =Yahoo! News |agency= [[Associated Press]] |accessdate=July 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAsked by [[Anderson Cooper]] in April 2018 whether he had ever heard President Trump tell a lie, Jordan said \"I have not\" and \"nothing comes to mind.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/383471-anderson-cooper-confronts-gop-lawmaker-you-havent-heard-the-president-lie|title=Anderson Cooper confronts GOP lawmaker: You haven't heard the president lie?|last=Savransky|first=Rebecca|date=April 17, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=April 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref> He also said, \"I don't know that [Mr. Trump has ever] said something wrong that he needs to [[Apology (act)|apologize]] for.\"<ref>Cooper, Anderson.  [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2018/04/17/rep-jim-jordan-comey-trump-lies-sot-ac.cnn \"Cooper to lawmaker: Does President Trump lie?\"] ''CNN''.  Video.</ref>\n\n====Donald Trump====\n\nJordan has been a stalwart supporter of President Donald Trump.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/06/us/politics/jim-jordan-sexual-misconduct.html|title=Jim Jordan Is Defiant as Allegations Mount, and Supporters Point to 'Deep State'|last=Edmondson|first=Catie|date=2018-07-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In December 2017, Jordan sought to discredit the FBI and Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]]'s [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/13/us/politics/trump-mueller-russia-republican-campaign.html|title=Justice Dept. Official Defends Mueller as Republicans Try to Discredit Him|last=Fandos|first=Nicholas|date=December 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 14, 2017|last2=Savage|first2=Charlie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Jordan questioned the impartiality of Mueller, and called on Deputy Attorney General [[Rod J. Rosenstein]] to use his authority to disband the Mueller investigation or create a second special counsel to simultaneously investigate Mueller himself.<ref name=\":0\" /> Rosenstein rejected the request, saying that he could not appoint another special counsel as there was not any credible allegation of any potential crime.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''The New York Times'' noted that Republicans increasingly criticised Mueller's investigation after it \"delivered a series of indictments to high-profile associates of the president and evidence that at least two of them are cooperating with the inquiry\".<ref name=\":0\" /> In July 2018, Jordan led efforts to impeach Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein as a way to shut down the special counsel's investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/396974-conservatives-moving-to-impeach-rosenstein-soon-report|title=Conservatives moving to impeach Rosenstein soon: report|last=Thomsen|first=Jacqueline|date=2018-07-13|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-07-15|language=en}}</ref> During a hearing on July 12, 2018, Jordan repeatedly interrupted FBI agent [[Peter Strzok]] while Strzok tried to explain that he couldn't answer specific questions in order to preserve the confidentiality of an ongoing investigation. Jordan's behavior caused committee Democrats to protest his tactics and to allow Strzok to respond. They also objected to Jordan's exceeding his allowed time for questioning. House Judiciary Committee chairman, Republican Bob Goodlatte, admonished Jordan for his repeated [[Interruption (speech)|interruptions]] of the witness.<ref>[https://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/jim-jordan-shouting-strzok-hearing Committee Erupts In Shouting As Jordan Trucks Over FBI Agent's Answer To His Question], ''[[The Hill (website)|The Hill]]'', Tierney Sneed, July 12, 2018. Retrieved July 18, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Jordan, along with [[Mark Meadows (North Carolina politician)|Mark Meadows]] called on the [[Department of Justice]] to \"review allegations that Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]] threatened to subpoena phone records and documents from a House Intelligence Committee staffer\". In their written request, the two wrote that in his use of investigative powers, Rosenstein had retaliated \"against rank-and-file (congressional) staff members\", therefore abusing his authority.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brufke |first1=Julie Grace |title=Freedom Caucus lawmakers call on DOJ to probe Rosenstein allegations |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/397340-freedom-caucus-lawmakers-call-on-doj-to-probe-rosenstein-allegations |website=The Hill |accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref> Talking to [[John Catsimatidis]] on [[WNYM]], Jordan said he would force a vote on the impeachment of Rosenstein if the DOJ does not deliver documents Congress requested.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thomsen |first1=Jacqueline |title=Jordan: If Rosenstein doesn't deliver, Meadows and I will force impeachment vote |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/399372-jordan-if-rosenstein-doesnt-deliver-meadows-and-i-will-force-impeachment-vote |website=The Hill |accessdate=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Jordan was criticized by House Judiciary Chairman [[Jerrold Nadler]] on the grounds that he allegedly used anti-Semitic messaging by spelling 2020 Presidential Candidate Tom Steyer's name with a \"$\" in place of an \"S\" on Twitter<ref>{{cite tweet |last=Jordan |first=Jim |user=Jim_Jordan |number=1102268353492721664 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305010212/https:/twitter.com/jim_jordan/status/1102268353492721664 |archivedate=5 March 2019 |title=C'mon @RepJerryNadler\u2014at least pretend to be serious about fact finding. Nadler feeling the heat big time. Jumps to Tom $teyer's conclusion\u2014impeaching our President\u2014before first document request. What a Kangaroo court. |date=3 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> while urging Nadler to resist calls for presidential impeachment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lafond |first1=Nicole |title=Nadler Accuses Jim Jordan Of Anti-Semitism Over '$teyer' Tweet, Jordan Denies |url=https://talkingpointsmemo.com/news/jerry-nadler-accuses-jim-jordan-anti-semitism-steyer-tweet |website=Talking Points Memo |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305085941/https://talkingpointsmemo.com/news/jerry-nadler-accuses-jim-jordan-anti-semitism-steyer-tweet |archivedate=March 5, 2019 |access-date=March 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/jewish-democrat-calls-republican-colleagues-tom-teyer-tweet-anti-semitic/|title=Jewish Democrat calls Republican colleague\u2019s \u2018Tom $teyer\u2019 tweet anti-Semitic|last=Kampeas|first=Ron|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Robert Mueller]]'s testimony to two congressional committees on July 24, 2019, Jordan asked Mueller why he never charged [[Joseph Mifsud]] with [[Making false statements|lying to the FBI]] while [[George Papadopoulos]] was charged for lying about Mifsud. Jordan said: \"Mifsud is the guy who told Papadopoulos [about Russian dirt], he was the guy who started it all, yet when the FBI interviews him, he lies three times. You don't charge him.\" Mueller responded: \"Well I can't get into it and it's obvious, I think, that we can't get into charging decisions.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Republicans confront Mueller with allegations of double standard in Russia probe |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/republicans-claim-double-standard-in-russia-probe |work=Fox News |date=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 23, 2019, Jordan and two dozen other Republicans staged a protest that delayed a [[Trump impeachment inquiry]] hearing. The coordinated action disrupted the [[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]] where Republican and Democratic congressional members planned to take testimony from Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense [[Laura Cooper]].<ref name=\"charge\">[https://www.al.com/news/2019/10/reps-mo-brooks-bradley-byrne-at-forefront-of-gop-charge-into-impeachment-room.html Reps. Mo Brooks, Bradley Byrne at forefront of GOP charge into impeachment room], ''[[AL.com]]'', Paul Gattis, October 23, 2019. Retrieved October 24, 2019.</ref>  The group staged a [[sit-in]] outside the [[Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility]] (SCIF) hearing room.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/house-republicans-literally-storm-the-impeachment-hearings|title=House Republicans Literally Storm the Impeachment Hearings|last=Stein|first=Sam Brodey{{!}}Sam|date=2019-10-23|access-date=2019-10-31|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"hearing\"/> Curiously, some of the Republicans who participated already had access to the hearings since the members of the House Oversight, Intelligence, and Foreign Affairs Committees were welcomed to attend and ask questions (which many did).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/10/republicans-scif-protest-and-the-politics-of-victimhood.html|title=Republicans Want Victimhood Without Being Victimized|last=Cheney-Rice|first=Zak|date=2019-10-25|website=Intelligencer|language=en-us|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n \nIn describing the \"stand-in\", Jordan said: \"the members have just had it, and they want to be able to see and represent their constituents and find out what's going on.\"<ref name=\"hearing\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/congress/chaotic-scene-as-republicans-disrupt-impeachment-deposition/2019/10/23/be96d8fc-f602-11e9-b2d2-1f37c9d82dbb_story.html Chaotic scene as Republicans disrupt impeachment deposition], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Michael Balsamo and Mary Clare Jalonick ''([[Associated Press]]),'' October 24, 2019. Retrieved October 24, 2019.</ref> The next day, Jordan appeared on Fox News and said that \"[[Adam Schiff]] is doing this unfair, partisan process in secret and our members finally said, 'Enough'...We're sooo frustrated. They reached a boiling point and these guys marched in and said 'we want to know what's going on.'\"<ref name=\"SCIF\">[https://www.foxnews.com/media/jim-jordan-defends-republicans-stormed-impeachment-inquiry-room Jim Jordan defends GOP lawmakers who stormed impeachment inquiry room], ''[[Fox News]]'', Charles Creitz, October 24, 2019. Retrieved October 26, 2019.</ref>\n\n[[House Homeland Security Committee]] chairman [[Bennie Thompson]] wrote to the House [[Sergeant-at-Arms|sergeant-at-arms]] about Jordan, Alabama representative [[Bradley Byrne]], and others, requesting that he take action regarding their \"unprecedented breach of security.\" South Carolina Republican senator [[Lindsey Graham]] admonished his House colleagues for their tactic, calling them \"nuts\" for having made a \"run on the SCIF.\"<ref name=\"SCIF\" /><ref>[https://www.aldailynews.com/chaotic-scene-as-republicans-disrupt-impeachment-deposition/ Chaotic scene as Republicans disrupt impeachment deposition], ''[[AL.com]]'', October 24, 2019. Retrieved October 26, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn November 8, 2019, Republicans made Jordan a temporary member of the House Intelligence Committee, allowing him to lead the defense for President Donald Trump's public impeachment hearings. GOP minority leader Kevin McCarthy tweeted about the move for Jordan, stating that Jordan's position was temporary and that [[Rick Crawford (politician)|Rep. Rick Crawford]] would rejoin the Intelligence Committee \"when this Democrat charade is over.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/republicans-jim-jordan-house-intelligence-impeachment-public-hearings-0283ef21-4a14-4d7c-a479-8c2078f96ff0.html|title=Republicans move Jim Jordan to House Intelligence Committee|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katv.com/news/local/rep-crawford-announces-temporary-resignation-from-the-house-intelligence-committee|title=Rep. Crawford announces temporary resignation from the House Intelligence Committee|last=KATV|date=2019-11-08|website=KATV|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\nJordan appeared in televised meetings not wearing a customary jacket but instead attired in shirtsleeves and a tie.<ref name=CSM/> He regularly interrupted testimony<ref name=CSM/> and consistently ignored time limits. Democratic Committee chair [[Adam Schiff]] interjected as Jordan questioned former Ukraine ambassador [[Marie Yovanovitch]], attempting to cut Jordan off after he exceeded his five-minute time limit. Schiff remonstrated, \"My indulgence is wearing out.\"<ref name=CSM/> Jordan responded, \"Our indulgence wore out with you a long time ago, Mr. Chairman.\"<ref name=CSM>[https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2019/1119/On-impeachment-Jim-Jordan-goes-for-the-takedown On impeachment, Jim Jordan goes for the takedown], ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', Jessica Mendoza, November 19, 2019. Retrieved December 2,2019.</ref> Afterward, Jordan repeated a Republican mantra: \"The Democrats have never accepted the will of the American people.\" \"They've been out to get the president since the day he was elected.\"<ref name=CSM/>\n\n====Environment====\nIn July 2008, Jordan was the first member of Congress to sign the \"No Climate Tax\" pledge drafted by the conservative political advocacy group [[Americans for Prosperity]], founded by the [[Koch brothers]].<ref>Davenport, Coral and Lipton, Eric [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/03/us/politics/republican-leaders-climate-change.html, \"How G.O.P. Leaders Came to View Climate Change as Fake Science\"], ''New York Times'', June 3, 2017, Retrieved June 3, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn Congress, Jordan voted to open the Outer Continental Shelf to oil drilling, prevent the EPA from regulating greenhouse gases, and bar greenhouse gases from Clean Air Act rules. He voted against enforcing limits on carbon dioxide ({{CO2}}) global warming pollution, tax credits for renewable electricity, tax incentives for renewable energy and energy conservation, and curtailing subsidies for oil and gas company exploration.<ref>[http://www.ontheissues.org/OH/Jim_Jordan_Energy_+_Oil.htm ''On the Issues: Jim Jordan on Energy and Oil''] Retrieved June 3, 2017.</ref>\n\n====Pharmaceutical industry====\nIn April 2019, Jordan warned pharmaceutical companies not to comply with a request for information sent by [[Elijah Cummings]], the Democratic chair of the House Oversight Committee, about how pharmaceutical companies set prescription drug prices.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/paulmcleod/republicans-warn-drug-companies-oversight-investigation|title=Republicans Are Warning Drug Companies Not To Cooperate With A Congressional Investigation|website=BuzzFeed News|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/cummings-accuses-republicans-obstructing-drug-prices-investigation/story?id=62465830|title=Cummings accuses Republicans of obstructing drug prices investigation|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/437585-oversight-republicans-accuse-cummings-of-partisan-drug-pricing|title=Oversight Republicans accuse Cummings of partisan drug pricing probe|last=Weixel|first=Nathaniel|date=2019-04-05|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref> Jordan suggested that Cummings would leak cherry-picked information in an attempt to harm the stock prices of pharmaceutical companies.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n====Planned Parenthood====\nJordan is against [[Planned Parenthood]] and supports ending Medicaid reimbursements to the organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefederalist.com/2015/09/29/a-quick-and-easy-guide-to-the-planned-parenthood-videos/ |title=A Quick and Easy Guide to the Planned Parenthood Videos |publisher=The Federalist |date=September 29, 2015 |accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Taxes====\nWhile serving in the Ohio Senate, Jordan supported the Tax and Expenditure Limitation Amendment, a state constitutional amendment that would require a vote of the people to raise taxes or increase spending over certain limits.<ref>{{cite web|last=Drewblade |first=James |url=http://toledoblade.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050114/NEWS24/501140415 |title=The Blade ~ Toledo Ohio |publisher=toledoblade.com |date= |accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Ohio State University abuse scandal==\n{{main|Ohio State University abuse scandal}}\nJordan was an assistant wrestling coach with the [[Ohio State University]]'s (OSU) [[Ohio State Buckeyes#Wrestling|wrestling program]] from 1987 to 1995.<ref name=\"wp172\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/jim-jordan-r-ohio/gIQAjcfUAP_print.html|title=Jim Jordan (R-Ohio)|date=29 September 2017|website=[[The Washington Post]]|quote=Career History: ... Assistant wrestling coach at The Ohio State University (OSU) (1987\u20131995) ... After graduating in 1986, Jordan returned to his home state to work as an assistant wrestling coach at OSU for nine years.|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Ohio State University began an independent investigation in April&nbsp;2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.osu.edu/investigation-underway-into-allegations-of-sexual-misconduct-against-former-wrestling-team-physician/|title=Investigation underway into allegations of sexual misconduct against former wrestling team physician|website=Investigation underway into allegations of sexual misconduct against former wrestling team physician|language=en-us|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> into allegations of [[Ohio State University abuse scandal|sexual misconduct by former wrestling team physician Richard Strauss]]; Strauss was the team physician during Jordan's tenure as assistant coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thelantern.com/2018/04/ohio-state-investigating-allegations-of-sexual-misconduct-by-former-wrestling-team-doctor/|title=Ohio State investigating allegations of sexual misconduct by former wrestling team doctor|last=Stankiewicz|first=Kevin|date=April 5, 2018|newspaper=The Lantern|accessdate=July 6, 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"kesling182\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-ohio-state-wrestlers-say-rep-jim-jordan-knew-of-team-doctors-alleged-misconduct-1530836633/|title=Former Ohio State wrestlers say Rep.&nbsp;Gym Jordan knew of team doctor's alleged misconduct|last1=Kesling|first1=Ben|date=5 July 2018|newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706031205/https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-ohio-state-wrestlers-say-rep-jim-jordan-knew-of-team-doctors-alleged-misconduct-1530836633/|archive-date=6 July 2018|url-status=live|last2=Peterson|first2=Kristina|quote=Former Ohio State wrestler Mike DiSabato has led a campaign to publicize Dr.&nbsp;Strauss's alleged wrongdoings for months and only recently began to criticize Mr.&nbsp;Jordan for allegedly ignoring athletes' concerns.|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Strauss committed suicide in 2005.<ref name=\"Strauss2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/rep-jim-jordan-returns-to-washington-as-scrutiny-over-alleged-sexual-abuse-at-ohio-state-intensifies/2018/07/08/4c772ef4-82c0-11e8-8553-a3ce89036c78_story.html|title=Representative Jim Jordan returns to Washington as scrutiny over alleged sexual abuse at The Ohio State intensifies|last1=Viebeck|first1=Elise|date=9 July 2018|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|access-date=9 July 2018|last2=Crites|first2=Alice|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn early June 2018, at least eight former wrestlers said that Jordan had been aware of, but did not respond to, allegations of sexual misconduct by Strauss.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/11/us/politics/jim-jordan-sexual-abuse-scandal.html|title=Unshaken by Abuse Scandal, Conservatives Are Sticking With Jim Jordan|last1=Edmonsen|first1=Catie|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 11, 2018|accessdate=July 27, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"viebeck182\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/rep-jim-jordan-faces-new-accusation-he-must-have-known-about-alleged-sexual-abuse-at-ohio-state/2018/07/07/5f21f5ca-822f-11e8-b9a5-7e1c013f8c33_story.html|title=Rep. Jim Jordan faces new accusation that he must have known about alleged sexual abuse at The Ohio State|last1=Viebeck|first1=Elise|work=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708050522/https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/rep-jim-jordan-faces-new-accusation-he-must-have-known-about-alleged-sexual-abuse-at-ohio-state/2018/07/07/5f21f5ca-822f-11e8-b9a5-7e1c013f8c33_story.html|archive-date=8 July 2018|url-status=live|last2=Crites|first2=Alice|quote=David Range ... said Jordan had to have known about alleged sexual misconduct by Richard Strauss ... because it happened regularly to team members and people talked about it.|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Jordan's locker was next to Strauss's, and Jordan spent so much time in the locker room that he created and awarded a \"King of the Sauna\" certificate to the member of the team who spent the most time in the sauna \"talking smack\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20180705/trump-says-he-doesnt-believe-allegations-against-jim-jordan-new-victim-emerges|title=Trump says he doesn't believe allegations against Jim Jordan; new victim emerges|last=Smola|first=Jennifer|website=The Columbus Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Jordan's congressional spokesman Ian Fury released a statement in which Ohio State wrestling coach [[Russ Hellickson]] reportedly said: \"At no time while Jim Jordan was a coach with me at Ohio State did either of us ignore abuse of our wrestlers. This is not the kind of man Jim is, and it is not the kind of coach that I was.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Tara|last=Goldshan|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/7/6/17536388/jim-jordan-ohio-state-sexual-abuse-accuser|title=Jim Jordan is accused of turning a blind eye to The Ohio State sexual abuse. Now he's attacking the accusers.|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|location=New York City|date=July 6, 2018|access-date=July 6, 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFormer wrestling team members David Range,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/rep-jim-jordan-faces-new-accusation-he-must-have-known-about-alleged-sexual-abuse-at-ohio-state/2018/07/07/5f21f5ca-822f-11e8-b9a5-7e1c013f8c33_story.html|title=Rep. Jim Jordan faces new accusation that he must have known about alleged sexual abuse at The Ohio State|last=Viebeck|first=Elise|last2=|first2=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708000509/https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/rep-jim-jordan-faces-new-accusation-he-must-have-known-about-alleged-sexual-abuse-at-ohio-state/2018/07/07/5f21f5ca-822f-11e8-b9a5-7e1c013f8c33_story.html|archive-date=2018-07-08|access-date=2019-10-31|last3=|first3=|last4=|first4=|last5=}}</ref> Mike DiSabato and Dunyasha Yetts asserted that Jordan knew of Strauss's misconduct. Yetts said \"For God\u2019s sake, Strauss\u2019s locker was right next to Jordan\u2019s and Jordan even said he\u2019d kill him if he tried anything with him\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/powerful-gop-rep-jim-jordan-accused-turning-blind-eye-sexual-n888386|title=Powerful GOP politician accused of turning blind eye to sexual abuse at Ohio State|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> No wrestlers have accused Jordan of sexual misconduct; however, Jordan was named as a defendant in a lawsuit against the university by four former wrestlers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/congressman-jim-jordan-knew-about-sex-abuse-former-wrestlers-say/lzfhebNU5mZ5WrRbfg3aFM/|title=Congressman Jim Jordan knew about sex abuse at OSU, former wrestlers say|last=Wehrman|first=Jessica|last2=Bischoff|first2=Laura A.|newspaper=[[Dayton Daily News]]|publisher=[[Cox Enterprises]]|location=Dayton, Ohio|date=July 3, 2018|access-date=October 31, 2019|last3=Smola|first3=Jennifer}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|first1=Rachael|last1=Bade|first2=John|last2=Bresnehan|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/07/06/jim-jordan-harassment-ohio-state-wrestling-699192|title='A cesspool of deviancy': New claims of voyeurism test Jordan denials|work=[[Politico]]|publisher=[[Capitol News Company]]|location=Arlington, Virginia|date=July 6, 2018|access-date=7 July 2018|language=en|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/jim-jordan-ohio-state-700578/|title=Rep. Jim Jordan Is Named in New OSU Sexual Abuse Lawsuit|last=Moser|first=Bob|date=July 18, 2018|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=July 20, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Several former wrestlers, including ex-UFC fighter [[Mark Coleman]], allege that Hellickson contacted two witnesses in an attempt to pressure them to support Jordan the day after they accused the congressman of turning a blind eye to alleged sexual abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelantern.com/2018/08/former-wrestlers-pressured-by-coach-to-support-jim-jordan/|title=Former wrestlers reportedly pressured by coach to support Jim Jordan|date=2018-08-01|website=The Lantern|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/former-ohio-state-wrestling-coach-urged-rep-jim-jordan-s-n896551|title=Former Ohio State wrestling coach urged Rep. Jim Jordan's accusers to recant, texts show|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref>\n\nJordan has refused to cooperate with investigations into Strauss.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Corky|last=Siemaszko|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/powerful-gop-rep-jim-jordan-accused-turning-blind-eye-sexual-n888386|title=Powerful GOP politician accused of turning blind eye to sexual abuse at Ohio State|website=[[NBC News]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|location=New York City|language=en|date=July 3, 2018|access-date=October 31, 2019}}</ref> Jordan described his accusers as \"pawns in a political plot\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2018/07/ohio-state-sexual-abuse-scandal-jim-jordan-implausibly-says-he-and-others-didnt-know.html|title=Now Jim Jordan Is Covering Up for His Ohio State Colleagues, Too|last=Saletan|first=William|date=July 30, 2018|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|publisher=The Slate Group|location=San Francisco, California|language=en|access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref> and insists that he did not even hear any locker room talk about Strauss or sexual abuse at OSU.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/ohio-lawmaker-wants-slap-congressman-jim-jordan-subpoena-n1052596|title=Ohio rep wants to put Rep. Jim Jordan on hot seat|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> In response to Jordan's denials, Mike DiSabato said: \"I considered Jim Jordan a friend. But at the end of the day, he is absolutely lying if he says he doesn't know what was going on.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/powerful-gop-rep-jim-jordan-accused-turning-blind-eye-sexual-n888386|title=Powerful GOP politician accused of turning blind eye to sexual abuse at Ohio State|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/jim-jordan-osu-wrestling-sexual-abuse-richard-strauss-1487016|title=Former wrestler alleges GOP Rep. Jim Jordan called him \"crying, groveling,\" wanted help covering up OSU abuse scandal|last=EST|first=James Crowley On 2/12/20 at 1:33 PM|date=2020-02-12|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nOn July 13, 2018, the editorial board of the ''[[Cleveland Plain Dealer]]'' asserted that \"Jim Jordan must acknowledge what he knew\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/opinion/2018/07/no_more_denials_jim_jordan_mus.html|title=No more denials. Jim Jordan must acknowledge what he knew: editorial|date=July 13, 2018|newspaper=[[The Plain-Dealer]]|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|location=Cleveland, Ohio|language=en|access-date=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, DiSabato filed a Title IX lawsuit against OSU. In one count of the court papers, DiSabato claimed that a second cousin of Jordan's attempted to \"intimidate and retaliate\" against DiSabato.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20180718/man-who-first-spoke-up-about-ohio-state-docs-sex-abuse-complicated-figure|title=Man who first spoke up about Ohio State doc's sex abuse a complicated figure|last=Rabinowitz|first=Bill|website=The Columbus Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/metro/2018/07/rep_jim_jordan_disputes_claims.html|title=Rep. Jim Jordan again disputes allegations he knew Ohio State wrestlers were sexually abused (videos)|last=Eaton|first=Sabrina|date=2018-07-05|website=cleveland|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> In 2019, DiSabato shared text messages with NBC News that were corroborated by another former wrestler<ref name=\"Siemaszko\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/former-osu-wrestler-who-accused-rep-jim-jordan-ignoring-abuse-n899416|title=Former OSU wrestler who accused Rep. Jim Jordan of ignoring abuse changes story|last=Siemaszko|first=Corky|date=August 9, 2018|website=[[NBC News]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|location=New York City|language=en|access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref> indicating that Jim Jordan, [[Russ Hellickson]], and high school wrestling coach Jeff Jordan (Jim Jordan's younger brother)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/end-era-jordan-retires-graham-wrestling-coach/whgP6n5jTVDnMXN6pFrc2H/|title=End of an era: Jordan retires as Graham wrestling coach|last=Pendleton|first=Marc|date=September 13, 2018|newspaper=[[Dayton Daily News]]|access-date=October 31, 2019|publisher=[[Cox Enterprises]]|location=Dayton, Ohio}}</ref> conspired to engage in witness tampering and intimidation when they called Coleman and Coleman's parents to pressure Coleman to recant his earlier accusation that Jordan was aware of the abuse.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\" />\n\nIn November 2019, a retired wrestling referee filed a lawsuit alleging that he had warned Jordan and Hellickson about Strauss' misconduct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/08/referee-told-rep-jim-jordan-about-ohio-state-dr-richard-strauss-sex-abuse-suit-says.html|title=Wrestling referee warned Rep. Jim Jordan about Ohio State doctor's sex misconduct, new lawsuit says|last=Dzhanova|first=Yelena|date=2019-11-08|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ohio-state-team-doctor-richard-strauss-abuse-allegations-referee-told-representitive-congress-jim-jordan-investigation-041337777.html|title=Referee files lawsuit, claims Rep. Jim Jordan ignored abuse allegations against Ohio State doctor|last=Young|first=Ryan|date=2019-11-08|website=sports.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref>  Jordan promptly dismissed the referee as \"another person making a false statement\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.limaohio.com/news/383183/jim-jordan-referees-claim-ridiculous |title=Jim Jordan: Referee's claim 'ridiculous' |author=Ellerbrock, Josh |date=November 12, 2019 |newspaper=Lima News |accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Adam DiSabato\u2014the brother of Mike DiSabato\u2014testified before the Ohio House Civil Justice Committee that \"Jim Jordan called me crying, crying. Groveling. On the 4th of July, begging me to go against my brother. Begging me. Crying for a half hour. That\u2019s the kind of cover-up that\u2019s going on there\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/jim-jordan-osu-wrestling-sexual-abuse-richard-strauss-1487016|title=Former wrestler alleges GOP Rep. Jim Jordan called him \"crying, groveling,\" wanted help covering up OSU abuse scandal|last=EST|first=James Crowley On 2/12/20 at 1:33 PM|date=2020-02-12|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/12/adam-disabato-rep-jordan-begged-him-deny-osu-abuse-claims/4741555002/|title=Ex-OSU wrestler: Rep. Jordan called \u2018crying, groveling, begging\u2019 to deny sexual abuse claims|last=Behrmann|first=Savannah|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref name=\"crying\">{{Citation|title=Former OSU Wrestler: Jim Jordan 'Called Me Crying' After Strauss Abuse Allegation {{!}} NBC News|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1Su8kTukkEg|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nJordan and his wife Polly live near [[Urbana, Ohio|Urbana]] in central [[Champaign County, Ohio|Champaign County]]. They were introduced by her brothers.  Jim Jordan explained in an interview with the ''Washington Examiner'' in 2014 that he competed in wrestling with Polly's brothers. He told the newspaper, \u201cI decided it would be a lot more fun wrestling with Polly than her brothers.\u201d They started dating when he was 13 and she was 14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/01/polly-jordan-jim-wife/|title=Polly Jordan, Jim Jordan's Wife: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|last=Laviola|first=Erin|date=2019-01-25|website=Heavy.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> They have four children and two grandchildren.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Eaton |first1=Sabrina |title=U.S. Rep. Jim Jordan of Ohio gains power among House conservatives |url=https://www.cleveland.com/open/index.ssf/2011/06/us_rep_jim_jordan_of_ohio_gain.html |website=cleveland.com |accessdate=February 28, 2019 |date=June 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Political campaigns==\n'''U.S. House of Representatives, Ohio 4th District'''\n\n2008 - defeated Mike Carroll.{{See also|2008 United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio#District 4}}\n2010 - defeated Doug Litt (D) and Donald Kissick (L).{{See also|2010 United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio#District 4}}\n2012 - defeated Jim Slone (D) and Chris Kalla (L).{{See also|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio#District 4}}\n2014 - defeated Janet Garrett (D).{{See also|2014 United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio#District 4}}\n2016 - defeated Janet Garrett (D).{{See also|2016 United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio#District_4}}\n2018 - defeated Janet Garrett (D).{{See also|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio#District_4}}\n\n==Electoral history==\n{|class=\"wikitable collapsible\"|state=collapse|\n|-bgcolor=#cccccc\n!colspan=19 style=\"background: #ccccff;\" |Election results of Jim Jordan<ref>{{cite news| title =Election Results| url =http://www.sos.state.oh.us/elections/Research/electResultsMain.aspx| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120815184807/http://www.sos.state.oh.us/elections/Research/electResultsMain.aspx| url-status =dead| archive-date =August 15, 2012| work =Ohio Secretary of State| accessdate =February 28, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n!Year\n!Office\n!Election\n!\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!\n!Opponent\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!\n!Opponent\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!\n|-\n|1998\n|[[Ohio House of Representatives]]\n|[[General election (U.S.)|General]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |[[Republican Party (United States)|R]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |23,763\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |68.36%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Robert Burns\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |[[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]\n|{{Party shadi